{"term":"1966","caseName":"Gilbert v. California","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1966/223","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 16, 1967","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/14914","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Jesse James Gilbert, Petitioner, versus California.","start":0,"stop":5.691,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court --","start":5.691,"stop":6.446,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mister --","start":6.446,"stop":6.656,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the termination of yesterday, I was informed -- I asked the marshal to inform me when ten minutes were left and I managed to go one minute over till nine, but I've concluded my opening argument.","start":6.656,"stop":14.512,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":14.512,"stop":17.247,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Mr. Sokolow.","start":17.247,"stop":20.327,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court.","start":20.327,"stop":24.259,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Mr. James will discuss the effect of the co-defendant's statements and I shall discuss the other issues commencing with the lineup.","start":24.259,"stop":33.582,"duration":9.32},{"text":"Relative to the lineup we believe the essential question is this, whether petitioner's right to the assistance of counsel for his defense was violated by his being placed in the lineup subsequent to his -- to the indictment when his counsel was not present at which lineup he was required to exhibit himself and speak for identification.","start":33.582,"stop":54.581,"duration":21},{"text":"Our answer briefly is that -- the right to the assistance of counsel did not apply to the lineup, there being no violation of the privilege against self-incrimination.","start":54.581,"stop":64.444,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand --","start":64.444,"stop":64.765,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":64.765,"stop":65.37,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand you to say he was compelled to speak after being put in the lineup?","start":65.37,"stop":73.709,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":73.709,"stop":76.635,"duration":2.93},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, by way of factual background, Mr. Gilbert was arrested in Philadelphia, February 26, 1964.","start":76.635,"stop":87.82,"duration":11.18},{"text":"He was indicted in this case on March 10th.","start":87.82,"stop":91.658,"duration":3.84},{"text":"He was not returned from Philadelphia to California until March 16th.","start":91.658,"stop":97.931,"duration":6.27},{"text":"Counsel was appointed March 18th, new counsel substituted in on March 24th.","start":97.931,"stop":103.989,"duration":6.06},{"text":"The lineup took place March 26.","start":103.989,"stop":107.133,"duration":3.14},{"text":"Three of the seven eyewitnesses to the robbery at the Mutual Savings and Loan in Alhambra which culminated in the killing of Officer Davis, related that they attended the lineup.","start":107.133,"stop":120.854,"duration":13.72},{"text":"Mrs. Riddle, Ms. Butler, and Mr. Clark at the penalty phase, the eight eyewitnesses who identified Gilbert in connection with various other robberies also related that they attended the lineup.","start":120.854,"stop":138.103,"duration":17.25},{"text":"From the record we have here, it appears that the ten or more so individuals in the lineup were asked to move and to speak for identification.","start":138.103,"stop":152.342,"duration":14.24},{"text":"What the -- I -- doesn't appear that Gilbert said anything of an incriminating nature that was --","start":152.342,"stop":161.618,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he know exactly what each was asked per se?","start":161.618,"stop":166.335,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Was there a question further how was it done, does the record tell us?","start":166.335,"stop":169.171,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The record is not as precise on that Your Honor.","start":169.171,"stop":172.276,"duration":3.11},{"text":"The only witnesses really that testified to any details of what happened were Ms. Butler, Mrs. Riddle, and Mr. Clark --","start":172.276,"stop":184.578,"duration":12.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, this was at the trial on guilt or innocence?","start":184.578,"stop":188.057,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"This was at the trial on guilt or innocence.","start":188.057,"stop":190.413,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The other eight testified only at the trial on penalty?","start":190.413,"stop":194.263,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":194.263,"stop":194.963,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the three --","start":194.963,"stop":195.557,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There were on -- excuse me.","start":195.557,"stop":197.845,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell us what the three who testified at the trial on guilt or innocence said they saw or heard?","start":197.845,"stop":205.077,"duration":7.23}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they were asked if -- Mr. Gilbert and the others were asked such question as, “Do you own an automobile?","start":205.077,"stop":214.582,"duration":9.5},{"text":"What type or what make is the automobile?","start":214.582,"stop":219.597,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Where were you arrested?”","start":219.597,"stop":221.528,"duration":1.93},{"text":"And -- now, in our record --","start":221.528,"stop":226.245,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he also tried to answer --","start":226.245,"stop":227.458,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":227.458,"stop":227.609,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- these questions, were all of the people in the lineup as you speak with Gilbert?","start":227.609,"stop":236.795,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Again, Your Honor, I don't -- it's my impression that the people in the lineup were all asked to move forward and to answer certain questions.","start":236.795,"stop":252.084,"duration":15.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Definitely.","start":252.084,"stop":253.266,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"And the --","start":253.266,"stop":254.118,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the record show them?","start":254.118,"stop":256.189,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The testimony?","start":256.189,"stop":257.858,"duration":1.67},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":257.858,"stop":258.719,"duration":0.86},{"text":"The -- I think we can glean that from the testimony of these three witnesses.","start":258.719,"stop":265.2,"duration":6.48},{"text":"Now as we pointed out in one of the --","start":265.2,"stop":266.177,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well an automobile is bigger than this --","start":266.177,"stop":268.283,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon sir.","start":268.283,"stop":269.179,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm so sorry, did an automobile figure in the crime?","start":269.179,"stop":276.108,"duration":6.93}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor in connection with the escape of the robbers and the -- relative to the search and seizure point as furnishing Officer Nixon with information on which to believe that at least two people had escaped in a certain automobile and then he found the wounded Mr. Weaver in a still another automobile --","start":276.108,"stop":301.076,"duration":24.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":301.076,"stop":301.954,"duration":0.88},{"text":"So -- but asking this man, asking petitioner whether he own an automobile is getting somewhat close to asking the question that had some relationship to guilt or innocence, is that right?","start":301.954,"stop":317.874,"duration":15.92}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that may be true Your Honor, but the point we believe is this that nothing that Mr. Gilbert responded as -- from our reversal of the record was brought to the attention of the jury through the witnesses who attended the lineup.","start":317.874,"stop":337.967,"duration":20.09},{"text":"Now, as we pointed out in a footnote to our brief, the federal case, Gilbert versus the United States pertaining to the same lineup does reflect that there was -- there were further matters brought out at the lineup and as counsel pointed out there -- in that -- in the opinion of the Court there that people in the audience called out, identifying numbers.","start":337.967,"stop":365.641,"duration":27.67},{"text":"However, Ms. Butler in our case and Mrs. Riddle did not have a recollection of that taking place, that is the people in the audience called out numbers, I'd refer very briefly to reporter's transcript page 157 and pages 356 and 57.","start":365.641,"stop":391.823,"duration":26.18}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"356?","start":391.823,"stop":392.782,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":392.782,"stop":393.771,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the purpose of compelling him to talk?","start":393.771,"stop":398.296,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I submit that it was for purpose for identification Your Honor.","start":398.296,"stop":403.458,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that routine in California that you ask them on the lineup, ask questions?","start":403.458,"stop":409.809,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe this is a traditional type of lineup Your Honor.","start":409.809,"stop":413.232,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the record in this case, I don't know if it comes to the record.","start":413.232,"stop":417.246,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The case was submitted on the typewritten copy of the record Your Honor.","start":417.246,"stop":422.188,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"So, we have just one copy (Voice Overlap) --","start":422.188,"stop":423.455,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":423.455,"stop":424.429,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"This information with the reference to these questions is at page 157, 356 --","start":424.429,"stop":432.205,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"And 357, yes.","start":432.205,"stop":433.938,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are the only reference to?","start":433.938,"stop":437.454,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- those are the only -- well, let me explained that that's the -- those are the places where Ms. Butler and Mrs. Riddle respectively testified to the effect that they did not recall hearing people from the audience that called out numbers.","start":437.454,"stop":459.803,"duration":22.35},{"text":"As far as --","start":459.803,"stop":460.609,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean calling out numbers?","start":460.609,"stop":461.863,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I don't understand.","start":461.863,"stop":463.995,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Were they -- he -- suspect numbered in the lineup?","start":463.995,"stop":467.536,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":467.536,"stop":468.919,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, who asked the questions, police officer or district attorney, who?","start":468.919,"stop":475.297,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"It was one of the officers, whether it was specifically a police officer or an FBI agent, I don't believe the record makes clear but it -- there was a moderator as it were who was asking the questions and directing the people who --","start":475.297,"stop":490.704,"duration":15.41}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"The questioning is not the purpose of identification of the voice, is it?","start":490.704,"stop":495.866,"duration":5.16},{"text":"It couldn't be if they're asking about their car?","start":495.866,"stop":499.815,"duration":3.95},{"text":"I suppose they were trying to find out if that was a car that the escapist (Inaudible).","start":499.815,"stop":507.392,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I -- the record doesn't go that far.","start":507.392,"stop":512.188,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But tell me Mr. Sokolow, suppose a question were put each one in the lineup, “Where you guilty of this crime of robbery of a certain savings bank which occurred in such and such day?”","start":512.188,"stop":525.486,"duration":13.3},{"text":"Would you be taking the position you are now if the record clearly showed that's what the question was even though the answer was not offered in evidence against the -- at the trial?","start":525.486,"stop":536.867,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would think that that would not be a proper question to ask if -- at the lineup --","start":536.867,"stop":544.438,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, my question was would the state --","start":544.438,"stop":545.561,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the lineup.","start":545.561,"stop":546.316,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- would the state be taking the same position that there was no Fifth Amendment issue involved if that had been the question?","start":546.316,"stop":553.987,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if that was not brought to the attention of the jury and if of course -- then we might be able to argue that perhaps that did not violate his --","start":553.987,"stop":568.284,"duration":14.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But what about the --","start":568.284,"stop":568.627,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Fifth Amendment (Voice Overlap) --","start":568.627,"stop":569.613,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the problem of -- what about the problem of fruits?","start":569.613,"stop":572.316,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Of what?","start":572.316,"stop":572.908,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of fruits, leads.","start":572.908,"stop":578.832,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, if that permeated to the eyewitnesses at the lineup, if it were shown and brought out that the -- then of course, I would think that there would be a Fifth Amendment question then.","start":578.832,"stop":594.673,"duration":15.84}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well one person --","start":594.673,"stop":594.77,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the (Voice Overlap) --","start":594.77,"stop":595.425,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the lineup said that --","start":595.425,"stop":597.1,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon sir.","start":597.1,"stop":598.032,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"One person at the lineup said he didn't that it can facilitate identification, wouldn't it?","start":598.032,"stop":604.783,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"If a person at the lineup said he did it?","start":604.783,"stop":607.25,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That its -- facilitate identification?","start":607.25,"stop":609.507,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":609.507,"stop":611.961,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"What was his answer that the -- it was his car, that he was in the car?","start":611.961,"stop":616.068,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't appear from our record Your Honor, what the answer was.","start":616.068,"stop":619.566,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean the record you referred me to doesn't appear?","start":619.566,"stop":623.76,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":623.76,"stop":624.512,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't know whether he answered it or not, did he?","start":624.512,"stop":627.138,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":627.138,"stop":627.959,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose -- I thought you were admitting the he answered it.","start":627.959,"stop":633.81,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he was -- the individuals at the lineup from our record were asked such question as, “Do you own any car?","start":633.81,"stop":644.872,"duration":11.06},{"text":"What is the make of the car?”","start":644.872,"stop":646.166,"duration":1.29},{"text":"And so on.","start":646.166,"stop":646.643,"duration":0.48},{"text":"What they specifically answered doesn't appear in the record at least.","start":646.643,"stop":653.33,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we know there might have several (Inaudible), I'm not going to answer that or if you (Inaudible).","start":653.33,"stop":659.189,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"True, but then, we think if that was the case that there is no reason why defense counsel at the trial could not have asked the witness just what did Mr. Gilbert answer.","start":659.189,"stop":672.309,"duration":13.12},{"text":"Or if the defense felt that there was an infringement of the Fifth Amendment rights that Mr. Gilbert himself could have taken the stand out of the presence of the jury on voir dire and testified to the effect that he was asked to make incriminating statements, but our record doesn't disclose that that was the case.","start":672.309,"stop":697.473,"duration":25.16}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you don't know whether he answered it all -- about it?","start":697.473,"stop":706.045,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe the record specifically shows that Your Honor.","start":706.045,"stop":710.538,"duration":4.49},{"text":"I mean the cross-examination, it's a -- is a rather sparse record as to the details of the lineup and the -- I think, the cross-examination was essentially the question -- what were the -- were you asked such question -- or where the people in the lineup asked such questions as, “What is -- did the defendant own a car?","start":710.538,"stop":730.151,"duration":19.61},{"text":"What is the make of the car?”","start":730.151,"stop":731.639,"duration":1.49},{"text":"And so on.","start":731.639,"stop":732.228,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How many of your practice do you need to the lineup question (Inaudible) the actual lineup procedure?","start":732.228,"stop":747.685,"duration":15.46}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- not to my knowledge Your Honor, to my knowledge.","start":747.685,"stop":754.304,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does a state contended that the lineup did not occur as was recorded in the opinion in the federal case?","start":754.304,"stop":769.39,"duration":15.09}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we're not contending that Your Honor, just that the witnesses in our case apparently didn't have the recollection of some of the witnesses in the federal case or that they were not cross-examined specifically in those respects as they were in the federal case.","start":769.39,"stop":791.672,"duration":22.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Were these the same witnesses in the federal case as in the state case?","start":791.672,"stop":800.76,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that probably on the penalty phase that they were, it's my impression from reading the federal circuit opinion that there was some similarity as to the things -- at least some of the witnesses, I think.","start":800.76,"stop":821.596,"duration":20.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on the question -- if it's a question of -- if you're contending that some lineups are legitimate and some are not legitimate, it would seem to me that it would be very important for us to know what happened here.","start":821.596,"stop":839.676,"duration":18.08},{"text":"And if the state knows and if the state agrees that what happened in the federal case is right, I would take that it would make such a concession here whether it happens to be in the record or not.","start":839.676,"stop":856.553,"duration":16.88},{"text":"What were interested in are the true facts of this situation, are we not?","start":856.553,"stop":860.836,"duration":4.28},{"text":"And if the federal court was right in finding what it did about these people declaring out the public, “That's the man” or “That's the man”, and someone else is the man.","start":860.836,"stop":873.015,"duration":12.18},{"text":"I would think the state would be willing to concede it here so, for the purposes of this case.","start":873.015,"stop":880.615,"duration":7.6},{"text":"Surely some investigation was made, was -- on this -- as to which version was true.","start":880.615,"stop":888.766,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it's our position that what was brought to the attention of the jury in this case by the witnesses who are present at the lineup was the crucial factor.","start":888.766,"stop":909.927,"duration":21.16},{"text":"It's -- it was our further feeling that actually, that is a record in a different case --","start":909.927,"stop":918.671,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":918.671,"stop":918.984,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that we in all candor did put -- have set forth in our brief the fact that the opinion does therein does refer to the same lineup.","start":918.984,"stop":929.575,"duration":10.59},{"text":"I would think perhaps it would be --","start":929.575,"stop":931.955,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But my point is simply this.","start":931.955,"stop":934.334,"duration":2.38},{"text":"If the state knows that that did happen as related in the federal case, and knows, then I suppose, we all would know, that if that was stated to the jury in this case, that it might have affected the verdict of the jury that the state would concede if it believes that to be the fact.","start":934.334,"stop":960.956,"duration":26.62},{"text":"Now if you don't believe it to be the fact, why -- entirely different thing.","start":960.956,"stop":966.638,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- I know from talking to a member of the United States' Attorney's Office that -- he told me that the testimony that appeared in the opinion in the case of Gilbert versus United States was in fact the testimony as it did appear in the record in that in that case.","start":966.638,"stop":997.238,"duration":30.6},{"text":"So, I would --","start":997.238,"stop":1000.398,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a -- what's the -- is that a federal habeas corpus?","start":1000.398,"stop":1004.44,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that was a prosecution for bank robberies Your Honor, a federal -- a prosecution --","start":1004.44,"stop":1009.888,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of a federally insured banker or a federal bank?","start":1009.888,"stop":1011.856,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1011.856,"stop":1013.017,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And it --","start":1013.017,"stop":1013.469,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"About four --","start":1013.469,"stop":1013.79,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"A separate prosecution?","start":1013.79,"stop":1015.749,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Your Honor.","start":1015.749,"stop":1016.891,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But the same lineup?","start":1016.891,"stop":1017.731,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1017.731,"stop":1018.283,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1018.283,"stop":1020.307,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And as I understood it, it grew out of the same arrest and this man when he was arrested, he said he would talk about other robberies but not about the one in California, isn't that right?","start":1020.307,"stop":1032.77,"duration":12.46}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, he --","start":1032.77,"stop":1033.622,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1033.622,"stop":1034.26,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and --","start":1034.26,"stop":1034.825,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that he would.","start":1034.825,"stop":1036.106,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Who made the --","start":1036.106,"stop":1036.124,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this show the answers?","start":1036.124,"stop":1037.468,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon sir?","start":1037.468,"stop":1038.06,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the federal reporter show the answers?","start":1038.06,"stop":1045.796,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The opinion in the federal case does -- I don't know that it shows that answers specifically as to what type of automobile and so forth.","start":1045.796,"stop":1061.53,"duration":15.73}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"You see, that's pretty a close question that -- and this lineup when you mingle with it, testimonial compulsion would -- makes it almost an impossible question.","start":1061.53,"stop":1073.205,"duration":11.67},{"text":"It's pretty an important point, factually, to me.","start":1073.205,"stop":1078.178,"duration":4.97},{"text":"Well, that's why I was asking you about whether it was unanswered.","start":1078.178,"stop":1084.383,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, who made any findings with respect to this matter in the federal case?The Court of Appeals or (Voice Overlap) --","start":1084.383,"stop":1091.033,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit Your Honor.","start":1091.033,"stop":1093.757,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But was there a reading in the testimony?","start":1093.757,"stop":1095.656,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Your Honor.","start":1095.656,"stop":1103.097,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Now, parenthetically, petitioner has suggested that a state statute was infringed relative to custody of prisoners insofar as taking Gilbert from the county jail to the lineup at the police station.","start":1103.097,"stop":1116.944,"duration":13.85},{"text":"Well, as we point out in our brief, the California Supreme Court indicated that if this was the case, it was immaterial.","start":1116.944,"stop":1125.187,"duration":8.24},{"text":"Now our further study of the record would indicate that in any event, Gilbert was not in state custody then, but in the custody of the federal authorities although being housed at the county jail.","start":1125.187,"stop":1138.524,"duration":13.34},{"text":"And we respectfully refer to the Court to pages 66 and 67 of Volume 1 which contains the pretrial proceedings, the previous reference was to the transcript containing the testimony which commences with Volume 6.","start":1138.524,"stop":1163.575,"duration":25.05},{"text":"We gather from the Schmerber opinion that traditionally, the lineup is considered an identification process -- that Schmerber reflects that the privilege against self-incrimination is not violated so long as -- at least by that compulsion which makes the accused the source of real or physical evidence and so long as he is required to move or to speak although extensively but only for the purpose of identification, he is exhibiting physical characteristics not communicating testimony only.","start":1163.575,"stop":1206.373,"duration":42.8},{"text":"We would submit that identification processes whether they be photographic, taking fingerprints, or displaying physical characteristics at a lineup are part and parcel of the people's preparation of the case, traditionally accomplished in private and that governmental interests of reasonable convenience and reasonable trading and preparing the people's case require that such preparation not be subject to curtailment or control by the defense.","start":1206.373,"stop":1236.687,"duration":30.31},{"text":"We reiterate that --","start":1236.687,"stop":1236.695,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this was also --","start":1236.695,"stop":1237.858,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if there is an infringement of the privilege against self incriminate -- oh, I didn't -- I'm sorry --","start":1237.858,"stop":1242.774,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1242.774,"stop":1244.075,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't hear you --","start":1244.075,"stop":1244.78,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon, I -- but this was part of the preparation in the case, wasn't it, it was post-indictment.","start":1244.78,"stop":1253.722,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1253.722,"stop":1253.866,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"It's part of the preparation in the case as distinguished from identification.","start":1253.866,"stop":1261.957,"duration":8.09},{"text":"In terms of trying to find out whether the person -- where there is enough basis for holding a person and charging a person with a crime.","start":1261.957,"stop":1274.3,"duration":12.34},{"text":"But -- and the -- that -- it's conceivable if that will make a difference.","start":1274.3,"stop":1279.188,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Can you tell us whether it's customary in California to have lineups after indictment, that most of them occur before the indictment?","start":1279.188,"stop":1290.818,"duration":11.63}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as to my own personal impression, that most of them occur before indictment.","start":1290.818,"stop":1296.081,"duration":5.26},{"text":"But in this case, of course, Mr. Gilbert was not returned from Philadelphia to California until after the indictment had taken place.","start":1296.081,"stop":1306.948,"duration":10.87}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1306.948,"stop":1312.358,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"We submit that if the accused is not entitled to assert a Fifth Amendment privilege at the lineup, then of course, it should be immaterial whether it occurred before or after the filing of the indictment.","start":1312.358,"stop":1330.703,"duration":18.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What happens in the area of California during lineups were (Inaudible)?","start":1330.703,"stop":1335.008,"duration":4.31},{"text":"If the man has a lawyer and the lawyer shows up and said, “I'd like to be present at the lineup”, would he be included or would he be excluded?","start":1335.008,"stop":1344.342,"duration":9.33}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he would be excluded Your Honor.","start":1344.342,"stop":1347.458,"duration":3.12},{"text":"At least I don't know of any incidences where he's been admitted and the -- in the Lopez case which we cite in our brief, a similar situation arose there and the counsel was excluded.","start":1347.458,"stop":1363.428,"duration":15.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any ordinary or usual procedure on the lineups in California, or isn't it on ad hoc basis?","start":1363.428,"stop":1377.094,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1377.094,"stop":1378.775,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What they've did that the police do just what they think the circumstances called for in having a lineup?","start":1378.775,"stop":1388.097,"duration":9.32},{"text":"This --","start":1388.097,"stop":1388.608,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I --","start":1388.608,"stop":1389.076,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any recognized practice?","start":1389.076,"stop":1393.613,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think they customarily put the individual in the lineup with enough others so that there can a fair testing of identification but as to the exact details on how they are conducted I would suppose they're -- perhaps on an ad hoc basis.","start":1393.613,"stop":1414.219,"duration":20.61},{"text":"Now, that --","start":1414.219,"stop":1416.004,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Here, I noticed that --","start":1416.004,"stop":1416.202,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I confess, I'm not --","start":1416.202,"stop":1417.11,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Here I noticed that not only did they put him in the lineup and have the -- this big audience out there watching them but they also required them to put on certain clothes.","start":1417.11,"stop":1430.141,"duration":13.03},{"text":"And in addition to that thing, they cause them to walk both fast and slow and then they asked them questions.","start":1430.141,"stop":1440.184,"duration":10.04},{"text":"Now, is it common in California to make a man dressed up for a -- in a way where -- to highly incriminate him in a lineup?","start":1440.184,"stop":1451.939,"duration":11.76}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it is perhaps customary for them to -- for all the people in the lineup to be as to -- try on articles of clothing and as I -- it seems to me that the -- this lineup here basically was quite similar again to that one in the Lopez case which we have cited in our brief which is a few years ago, and another California lineup, much along the same lines.","start":1451.939,"stop":1484.699,"duration":32.76}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you get in that if you can't identify?","start":1484.699,"stop":1488.54,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon sir.","start":1488.54,"stop":1489.865,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you get into that even if you don't know the identity of the defendant?","start":1489.865,"stop":1495.64,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in this case, the various witnesses have been shown photographs.","start":1495.64,"stop":1509.432,"duration":13.79}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"You're just framing it up, wouldn't --","start":1509.432,"stop":1510.84,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"This would be framing it up -- yes, Your Honor.","start":1510.84,"stop":1520.527,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Now, assuming but not conceding that some legal impropriety might have prepped into the lineup, would that invalidate the testimony of the witnesses who identified Gilbert, we submit it would not as was pointed out in the Silverthorn Lumber Company case that knowledge of the facts is gained from an independent source they may be proved as any others.","start":1520.527,"stop":1547.466,"duration":26.94},{"text":"The eyewitnesses here did not come into existence as such because they attended the lineup but because they were present when an offense was committed.","start":1547.466,"stop":1556.853,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask Mr. Sokolow, I finally get -- have this Court of Appeals' opinion which is very confusing business trips, so many different ones here.","start":1556.853,"stop":1565.745,"duration":8.89},{"text":"So I'd like to ask you, and this opinion here of Judge Browning, this is a dissent on the issue of lineup.","start":1565.745,"stop":1572.075,"duration":6.33},{"text":"As I read Judge Duniway's opinion, the holding there was no motion had been made to suppress and so forth.","start":1572.075,"stop":1577.509,"duration":5.43},{"text":"It's not very informative about what happened at the lineup.","start":1577.509,"stop":1580.997,"duration":3.49},{"text":"Now Judge Browning's opinion has this short paragraph, “Approximately 13 men including appellant appeared on stage, the prisoners were identified by number.","start":1580.997,"stop":1592.22,"duration":11.22},{"text":"They were required to pose the center of the stage individually, turn, try on various articles of clothing, and answered questions including whether they owned an automobile, where they were arrested, and whether when arrested, they were armed.","start":1592.22,"stop":1607.626,"duration":15.41},{"text":"They were required to say certain phrases used during the robberies, “Freeze, this is a stickup.","start":1607.626,"stop":1613.363,"duration":5.74},{"text":"This is a holdup.","start":1613.363,"stop":1614.695,"duration":1.33},{"text":"This is a heist.","start":1614.695,"stop":1616.194,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Don't anyone move.","start":1616.194,"stop":1617.766,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Empty your cash drawer.”","start":1617.766,"stop":1619.616,"duration":1.85},{"text":"To shout these phrases and repeat them in a quiet voice while standing still and while walking both normally and at a rapid pace”.","start":1619.616,"stop":1628.013,"duration":8.4},{"text":"Now, does that describe what actually happened if you understand it at the lineup?","start":1628.013,"stop":1633.939,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that occur -- accords also with the majority opinion -- the opinion of the Judge Duniway in the same case and I certainly acknowledge that there was testimony in that federal case to that effect.","start":1633.939,"stop":1650.214,"duration":16.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But, what was -- I'm -- is the testimony in the state case like this?","start":1650.214,"stop":1656.073,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1656.073,"stop":1656.711,"duration":0.64},{"text":"It's not merely so extensive.","start":1656.711,"stop":1658.979,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though it's the same lineup?","start":1658.979,"stop":1660.512,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Same lineup.","start":1660.512,"stop":1661.917,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they don't ask the same questions with each number, do they?","start":1661.917,"stop":1666.985,"duration":5.07},{"text":"I suppose they'd asked number 1 about his -- what they thought he was doing, and number 2 about his, trying to correlate them, won't you?","start":1666.985,"stop":1677.241,"duration":10.26}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't think --","start":1677.241,"stop":1677.489,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"So that -- this paragraph here wouldn't necessarily refer to this case here, would it?","start":1677.489,"stop":1684.069,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't think we can say specifically from either record precisely what each individual in there.","start":1684.069,"stop":1693.207,"duration":9.14}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"It's unfortunate if you didn't have a record.","start":1693.207,"stop":1696.328,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Is there any other record besides the one you have?","start":1696.328,"stop":1699.95,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, not that I know of.","start":1699.95,"stop":1707.817,"duration":7.87},{"text":"I -- we would like to stress that trial judge's observations as to one of the eyewitnesses, Ms. Butler -- he said -- I am saying she comes into the courtroom here regardless, if you hadn't any show up here at all, and this by the way is set out in our brief, she comes into the courtroom here and positively identifies the defendant.","start":1707.817,"stop":1733.44,"duration":25.62},{"text":"I would think, if I were in the robbery she was in, I would have think that -- I would have a pretty -- I -- good idea of who did it when I saw him in the courtroom and I think she has.","start":1733.44,"stop":1745.5,"duration":12.06},{"text":"And we submit that as to all of the eyewitnesses who identified Gilbert in the courtroom that their testimony reflected the definite opportunity on the part of each one to observe the perpetrator of the particular robbery and that the people were manifestly relying on those in court identifications.","start":1745.5,"stop":1768.843,"duration":23.34},{"text":"But going to the --","start":1768.843,"stop":1770.655,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Sokolow if --","start":1770.655,"stop":1771.592,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1771.592,"stop":1773.034,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If all they can do at the trial is to test the recollection and the identification of the witness, is there anyway that an illegal lineup could be tested, shows to prevent it having tainted the case?","start":1773.034,"stop":1799.925,"duration":26.89}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, I --","start":1799.925,"stop":1800.758,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How could that be done?","start":1800.758,"stop":1802.161,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I submit that the defense had made a motion to exclude any testimony relating to the lineup or derived from it on the -- and asked that the defendant be permitted to take the stand on voir dire examination outside the presence of the jury to relate just exactly what the infringement was.","start":1802.161,"stop":1825.714,"duration":23.55},{"text":"And we do not have that in our case here.","start":1825.714,"stop":1830.511,"duration":4.8},{"text":"Now going on then to the handwriting exemplars, as counsel for petitioner indicated yesterday, there is a certain similarity between the two issues.","start":1830.511,"stop":1845.482,"duration":14.97},{"text":"By way of factual background, and FBI agent, Mr. Dean arrested Gilbert about 9 PM, February 26th in Philadelphia.","start":1845.482,"stop":1855.508,"duration":10.03},{"text":"Gilbert was surprised of his rights to an attorney but he did not have to make any statements and any statement he made to be used against him in courts.","start":1855.508,"stop":1863.836,"duration":8.33},{"text":"He was transported downtown about three miles from the arrest scene.","start":1863.836,"stop":1868.989,"duration":5.15},{"text":"At FBI headquarters, he refused to discuss his activities on the east or west coast indicating he wanted to obtain counsel before making any statements.","start":1868.989,"stop":1879.355,"duration":10.37},{"text":"At 10 PM, another agent, Mr. Shanahan spoke that Mr. Gilbert again, telling him he did not have to make any statements without the advice of an attorney and any statement he made could be used against him in a court of law.","start":1879.355,"stop":1898.654,"duration":19.3},{"text":"Shanahan asked Gilbert if he'd like to talk to him and Gilbert said he would, providing it did not pertain to the case in California.","start":1898.654,"stop":1907.696,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Shanahan testified that he interviewed Gilbert according on that basis.","start":1907.696,"stop":1914.517,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Shanahan was interested in some robberies in Philadelphia.","start":1914.517,"stop":1919.206,"duration":4.69},{"text":"He was working on them.","start":1919.206,"stop":1920.811,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Demand notes had been used in consummating those robberies.","start":1920.811,"stop":1926.213,"duration":5.4},{"text":"They have been passed to the tellers.","start":1926.213,"stop":1927.896,"duration":1.68},{"text":"He asked Gilbert if Gilbert would give him some samples of his hand printing and Gilbert agreed and did so.","start":1927.896,"stop":1938.245,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Now, Shanahan testified he had no information.","start":1938.245,"stop":1943.161,"duration":4.92},{"text":"These hand printing exemplars were to be used later on in Los Angeles.","start":1943.161,"stop":1950.162,"duration":7},{"text":"However, it was FBI policy to secure hand printing samples of all suspects in robberies and keep them on file here in Washington.","start":1950.162,"stop":1961.258,"duration":11.1},{"text":"Keep them on file of samples of -- handwriting samples of bank robberies throughout the country.","start":1961.258,"stop":1970.192,"duration":8.93},{"text":"It was testified that --","start":1970.192,"stop":1971.323,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sokolow --","start":1971.323,"stop":1971.834,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1971.834,"stop":1972.574,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you if this is a fair statement of the state's position.","start":1972.574,"stop":1979.699,"duration":7.13},{"text":"This man was arrested and was asked to make a statement, he said, “I will not make a statement about anything occurred here in California.","start":1979.699,"stop":1992.365,"duration":12.67},{"text":"I'm willing to discuss with you any charges against me in other states”.","start":1992.365,"stop":1999.092,"duration":6.73},{"text":"And pursuant to that, they held this lineup and had these witnesses at the California robbery in the audience that was viewing the lineup and that these questions that were asked of him pertained to the California robbery and not to the ones in the other states?","start":1999.092,"stop":2026.438,"duration":27.35}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, well Your Honor, the --","start":2026.438,"stop":2026.498,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that (Voice Overlap) of it or am I mistaken in that -- in those facts?","start":2026.498,"stop":2032.381,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I would respectfully submit that Your Honor would be mistaken in that the -- the lineup took place at quite some while after this interview.","start":2032.381,"stop":2040.348,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg pardon?","start":2040.348,"stop":2041.153,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The lineup took place some while after this interview at the FBI headquarters in Philadelphia.","start":2041.153,"stop":2047.426,"duration":6.27},{"text":"The lineup was March 26 and this interview where the handwriting exemplars were given was February 26, in other words about a month earlier.","start":2047.426,"stop":2062.635,"duration":15.21},{"text":"It was on February 26th that Gilbert said in effect he did not want to discuss anything about California but would be willing to talk about Philadelphia and that Shanahan indicated that he is interested in some bank robberies that had occurred in Philadelphia.","start":2062.635,"stop":2082.185,"duration":19.55},{"text":"He suspected that Gilbert might be involved in them and would Gilbert talk about those loosely or freely interpreting the record.","start":2082.185,"stop":2091.627,"duration":9.44},{"text":"And it was in the course of that discussion that Gilbert gave the hand printing samples and the handwriting expert gave his qualified opinion that there was a link between the hand printing samples and the writing or printing on a diagram of the robbery scene that was found at -- in Gilbert's apartment in the Los Angeles area.","start":2091.627,"stop":2122.893,"duration":31.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- so the lineup was before he made that statement, was it that --","start":2122.893,"stop":2129.114,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Subsequently, Your Honor.","start":2129.114,"stop":2130.203,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a --","start":2130.203,"stop":2130.498,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"About a month subsequently.","start":2130.498,"stop":2131.564,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2131.564,"stop":2131.773,"duration":0.21},{"text":"Well, had he ever changed his statement to the police as to what situation he is willing to talk about?","start":2131.773,"stop":2147.948,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe the record which -- well, there was some evidence -- effort by the people as I recall to introduce some statements that Gilbert made and the Court excluded those statements.","start":2147.948,"stop":2168.514,"duration":20.57},{"text":"I would have to double check them.","start":2168.514,"stop":2171.865,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Of course they were excluded but I think they were excluded on the basis that Gilbert at that time definitely indicated he wanted a counsel.","start":2171.865,"stop":2185.053,"duration":13.19},{"text":"Now, whether that would give the answer to Your Honor's questions, I don't this moment recall.","start":2185.053,"stop":2195.942,"duration":10.89},{"text":"Well, the -- there was testimony at any rate that the filing of the hand printing samples here in Washington was in the same category as taking and keeping fingerprints on file.","start":2195.942,"stop":2210.565,"duration":14.62},{"text":"And we would submit that that's an illuminating piece of testimony that -- it's in the same category as taking and keeping fingerprints on file.","start":2210.565,"stop":2219.643,"duration":9.08},{"text":"In other words, it points up the identification aspect of taking handwriting exemplars and lends emphasis to our position that handwriting is no more and no less than an essential, physical characteristic.","start":2219.643,"stop":2251.417,"duration":31.77},{"text":"We would urge that the giving of the exemplars in the case at bar involves no testimonial compulsion which is a predicate for invoking the privilege against self-incrimination.","start":2251.417,"stop":2263.708,"duration":12.29},{"text":"Gilbert was not required to verify the authenticity of this hand printing on the exemplars that was provided by Agent Shanahan who's -- for whom Gilbert filled out the exemplars, and he was not -- Gilbert was not compelled to disclose that the writing on the diagram was his.","start":2263.708,"stop":2281.8,"duration":18.09},{"text":"That was proved to a qualified extent by the handwriting expert.","start":2281.8,"stop":2289.091,"duration":7.29},{"text":"So, we urged that giving exemplars as in the case at bar involves no violation of the privilege against self-incrimination, a privilege which invokes the right to the assistance of counsel.","start":2289.091,"stop":2304.046,"duration":14.95},{"text":"We'd like to say a few words about the search and seizure point by way of factual background, just after the shooting of Officer Davis at the Mutual Savings and Loan, a businessman in the area saw two men running out of the Savings and Loan and then shortly saw a car drive away.","start":2304.046,"stop":2329.33,"duration":25.28},{"text":"Now, this man told Officer Nixon that the persons -- two persons were in a white Pontiac and gave Nixon the license number on a slip of paper, Nixon broadcasts this information over his police radio then went in pursuit.","start":2329.33,"stop":2343.432,"duration":14.1},{"text":"Soon afterward, another person told Nixon that two men had left a white Pontiac and driven away an Oldsmobile.","start":2343.432,"stop":2350.996,"duration":7.56},{"text":"Soon after, Nixon came upon a white Pontiac that was parked and the license number tallied with that on the slip of paper.","start":2350.996,"stop":2359.693,"duration":8.7},{"text":"And then soon afterward, he saw a Chevrolet automobile in which contained Mr. Weaver who as it developed was mortally wounded.","start":2359.693,"stop":2373.005,"duration":13.31},{"text":"Well, Weaver was taken to the hospital, interviewed by FBI Agent Norton.","start":2373.005,"stop":2379.407,"duration":6.4},{"text":"After -- and Norton kept in contact with his office relative to the information that Weaver was giving which information lead the authorities to this apartment for the Hawaiian sounding name near Los Feliz and Riverside Drive and the pursuit was so hot that Gilbert or Mr. Flood as he was known at the apartment was apparently just leaving as the FBI Agent Kiel arrived.","start":2379.407,"stop":2412.907,"duration":33.5},{"text":"Other officers arrives shortly including Agent Schlatter, where we have testimony in the records set out in our brief as to Schlatter's frame of mind when he entered the apartment with a key.","start":2412.907,"stop":2429.4,"duration":16.49},{"text":"It was his frame of mind that the authorities had information that there were three robbers, that one was wounded and accounted for, that would be Weaver, one had left a few minutes earlier, and a third was unaccounted for and might very well be in that apartment right then and there.","start":2429.4,"stop":2446.221,"duration":16.82},{"text":"And of course, Mr. Schlatter was aware that a police officer had been shot, and he explained in his testimony the authorities were going into a place where there is a man who had just participated in a bank robbery and might be armed, and it was their intention to take that man into custody.","start":2446.221,"stop":2465.048,"duration":18.83},{"text":"So we urged that the exigent circumstances of the robbers fleeing in a hot pursuit justified the entry into the apartment by means of the key unannounced.","start":2465.048,"stop":2474.763,"duration":9.72},{"text":"Now, once they were inside, the authorities observed some objects in open view and -- or the -- with the exception of some photographs, these were taken later on in connection with the issuance of search warrants.","start":2474.763,"stop":2491.57,"duration":16.81},{"text":"Now, the only objects taken initially --","start":2491.57,"stop":2494.342,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean they were taken pursuant to a warrant with the exception of the photographs?","start":2494.342,"stop":2498.416,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2498.416,"stop":2499.094,"duration":0.68},{"text":"A search warrant was issued later in that afternoon and they were taken pursuant to that.","start":2499.094,"stop":2503.387,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2503.387,"stop":2504.249,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2504.249,"stop":2504.661,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they make any search of the house at this particular time?","start":2504.661,"stop":2510.306,"duration":5.64},{"text":"The first time they were there?","start":2510.306,"stop":2511.125,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- well, we have the testimony of Mr. Crowley (ph) who testified -- testimony goes that he arrived at this apartment after he had been searched for people.","start":2511.125,"stop":2524.84,"duration":13.72},{"text":"He was instructed to look for anything that could be used to identify or continue the pursuit of the person without conducting a detailed search.","start":2524.84,"stop":2533.726,"duration":8.89},{"text":"And on top of the dresser in the bedroom, he saw this envelop containing the name of the photographic studio and it appeared to contain some objects and looked inside and saw that there were these photographs of an individual.","start":2533.726,"stop":2551.981,"duration":18.26},{"text":"It was compared with a mug shot and the indication was that it was of Mr. Gilbert and the -- these small photos, passport tagged photos were taken out to the scene of the robbery and killing of Officer Davis, the Savings and Loan, and the reproduction of one of these photographs was shown to various witnesses.","start":2551.981,"stop":2579.527,"duration":27.55},{"text":"And we submit that the reproduction of that photograph exhibited to the witnesses there that same day could very well confirm or disprove the validity of Weaver's lead and point the direction in which the authorities should concentrate their efforts to apprehend the man who fled after robbing the Savings and Loan and killing Officer Davis --","start":2579.527,"stop":2606.291,"duration":26.76}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sokolow, what were the items seized on the search warrant subsequent?","start":2606.291,"stop":2610.663,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"There was ammunition clip, some money, some --","start":2610.663,"stop":2621.056,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"A drawing?","start":2621.056,"stop":2621.538,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"A drawing of the -- there was a notebook there containing a diagram of the Savings and Loan area.","start":2621.538,"stop":2628.406,"duration":6.87},{"text":"There were some --","start":2628.406,"stop":2628.516,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it the -- if the initial search was -- its not the -- there was no probable cause in the part of the officers to know that stuff was there.","start":2628.516,"stop":2639.788,"duration":11.27},{"text":"They didn't know anything about until they got into the apartment they sought.","start":2639.788,"stop":2642.457,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true Your Honor.","start":2642.457,"stop":2643.505,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And I take it, if the original entry was illegal, the seizure is not -- the better because, ultimately you've got a search warrant, isn't it?","start":2643.505,"stop":2654.535,"duration":11.03}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's true Your Honor.","start":2654.535,"stop":2657.666,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the meaning of the --","start":2657.666,"stop":2657.883,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we --","start":2657.883,"stop":2658.884,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Court of Appeals go (Inaudible) on a -- on the hot pursuit of what was out there?","start":2658.884,"stop":2664.819,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals, the -- they emphasized the hot pursuit, the exigent circumstances.","start":2664.819,"stop":2672.528,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"The same with the California (Voice Overlap) --","start":2672.528,"stop":2674.695,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, so they elaborated and went into, I would say a lengthier discussion of it.","start":2674.695,"stop":2682.374,"duration":7.68},{"text":"Now, the Court of Appeals was unanimous in that phase of its opinion.","start":2682.374,"stop":2687.08,"duration":4.71},{"text":"That was the phase of the opinion that was written by Judge Browning, then the rest of the prevailing opinion, I might say was written by Judge Duniway and concurred in the -- by the other Circuit Judge --","start":2687.08,"stop":2705.163,"duration":18.08}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Barnes","start":2705.163,"stop":2705.203,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and then Judge --","start":2705.203,"stop":2707.126,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Barnes, wasn't it?","start":2707.126,"stop":2708.014,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Barnes, and then Judge Browning dissented as to the lineup.","start":2708.014,"stop":2713.379,"duration":5.36},{"text":"That's some other --","start":2713.379,"stop":2713.583,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he -- he did not dissent as to the search?","start":2713.583,"stop":2715.78,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the Court there was in accord as to the search.","start":2715.78,"stop":2719.57,"duration":3.79},{"text":"Thank you Your Honors.","start":2719.57,"stop":2720.881,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you one question?","start":2720.881,"stop":2721.917,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2721.917,"stop":2724.525,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your position that the state or the Government can take the person and put him in a lineup and compel him to answer questions which might be used against him or which might supply the fruits of -- or using it against him and if that would be legal?","start":2724.525,"stop":2750.785,"duration":26.26}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that would be proper where if he was compelled to incriminate himself at the lineup Your Honor.","start":2750.785,"stop":2757.699,"duration":6.91},{"text":"It's a --","start":2757.699,"stop":2758.701,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what I'm talking about, compel either to write something for the state to use against him on either an investigation or in a trial are compelled to make statements for the state to use against him in connection with the -- his case?","start":2758.701,"stop":2776.082,"duration":17.38}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't think he should be compelled to say anything or write anything like, “Yes, I am guilty of this crime”, but as far as speaking for voice identification --","start":2776.082,"stop":2787.89,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's the --","start":2787.89,"stop":2787.968,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or write a sample of --","start":2787.968,"stop":2789.312,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the difference in that if that's to be used against him?","start":2789.312,"stop":2795.059,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we would advert --","start":2795.059,"stop":2797.885,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the difference of a direct confession and statement of facts which will help the state folds the link of its chains about him?","start":2797.885,"stop":2810.353,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, we would say that basically this is -- just in a nature of an identification process basically such as taking fingerprint impressions of the -- that's been considered as distinct from -- or not as critical shall we say as requiring the individual to make statements that are going to incriminate him at the trial.","start":2810.353,"stop":2843.393,"duration":33.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you agree that the officers did here -- get this man, take him into a lineup, and then compel him to answer questions or compel him to write something which was helpful to the state in bringing about his conviction.","start":2843.393,"stop":2861.503,"duration":18.11}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"It was helpful to the state in identifying him, yes, in that sense Your Honor.","start":2861.503,"stop":2869.156,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The fellow -- that man has to be identified before he can be charged I suppose, so that's to -- helping to get evidence to prove that he is guilty of a crime, isn't it?","start":2869.156,"stop":2882.619,"duration":13.46}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes sir.","start":2882.619,"stop":2883.712,"duration":1.09},{"text":"Yes Your Honor, in that sense, I would agree.","start":2883.712,"stop":2886.612,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Where was the compulsion with respect to the handwriting for example?","start":2886.612,"stop":2891.814,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps the compulsion isn't the most appropriate word to use.","start":2891.814,"stop":2900.016,"duration":8.2},{"text":"Perhaps he was --","start":2900.016,"stop":2901.01,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's (Voice Overlap) --","start":2901.01,"stop":2901.241,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"He was requested to give handwriting exemplars and the record reflects that he voluntarily gave them.","start":2901.241,"stop":2910.3,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, you mean it's compulsion in the Miranda sense and that there was a question or a suggestion in the context of the -- that the context of a custody that -- is that as much compulsion as there was that (Voice Overlap) --","start":2910.3,"stop":2926.846,"duration":16.55}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's not -- it's not the -- you might say that perhaps the -- it might be considered compulsion in that sense.","start":2926.846,"stop":2935.585,"duration":8.74},{"text":"But it's not -- we would certainly argue that it was not incriminating in the Miranda sense.","start":2935.585,"stop":2940.781,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how would --","start":2940.781,"stop":2941.334,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"As I --","start":2941.334,"stop":2942.283,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I know that, but how about compulsion?","start":2942.283,"stop":2944.092,"duration":1.81},{"text":"That's what I'm --","start":2944.092,"stop":2944.657,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know if I used the most apt expression in saying he was --","start":2944.657,"stop":2948.897,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2948.897,"stop":2949.16,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- compelled to speak, he had --","start":2949.16,"stop":2950.415,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you concede -- can't you concede that sure, he is compelled.","start":2950.415,"stop":2954.067,"duration":3.65},{"text":"Of course he's compelled, even the Fifth Amendment says that, but the issue is what is compelled from him is something that violates the Fifth Amendment.","start":2954.067,"stop":2962.379,"duration":8.31},{"text":"Is it testimonial --","start":2962.379,"stop":2964.248,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- well I --","start":2964.248,"stop":2964.834,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the --","start":2964.834,"stop":2965.121,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Your Honors, it's of --","start":2965.121,"stop":2966.827,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I think there's still a question of compulsion.","start":2966.827,"stop":2969.457,"duration":2.63},{"text":"I agree with you that there is a -- the other question too.","start":2969.457,"stop":2972.338,"duration":2.88},{"text":"When did this trial take place?","start":2972.338,"stop":2974.958,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"The trial started a little before Escobedo came down Your Honor and would be our --","start":2974.958,"stop":2982.924,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And if it's only compulsion in the sense that these events took place in that -- in custody --","start":2982.924,"stop":2990.007,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2990.007,"stop":2990.307,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2990.307,"stop":2990.603,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words there was no --","start":2990.603,"stop":2991.383,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that nobody forced (Voice Overlap) --","start":2991.383,"stop":2991.817,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- there was no force or --","start":2991.817,"stop":2993.111,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Nobody really forced anybody to do anything?","start":2993.111,"stop":2995.657,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was no --","start":2995.657,"stop":2996.204,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no physical or mental or (Voice Overlap) --","start":2996.204,"stop":2997.308,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was no (Inaudible) situation.","start":2997.308,"stop":2999.886,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That have -- if the only reason is that you would say he's compelled is in the Miranda sense, then the question arises whether a new rule like Miranda would apply to a -- to this case?","start":2999.886,"stop":3012.273,"duration":12.39}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3012.273,"stop":3013.468,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that's right.","start":3013.468,"stop":3014.232,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But they took him from his cell, did they not?","start":3014.232,"stop":3017.37,"duration":3.14},{"text":"Ordered him to go down, to go through this proceeding, did he go down there of his own accord and say I want to go down to be viewed?","start":3017.37,"stop":3031.211,"duration":13.84}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Again, the record doesn't clearly show that.","start":3031.211,"stop":3035.697,"duration":4.49},{"text":"He certainly didn't take the stand for voir dire testimony and the -- say that I objected.","start":3035.697,"stop":3041.619,"duration":5.92},{"text":"Now, at the -- there's a discussion between Court and counsel at recorder's transcript pages 194 and 5 in which defense counsel says -- said to the Court that my client has told me that he told the marshals that he didn't want to go to the lineup for that was a Fifth Amendment violation and they did -- I'm interpreting the record freely here, not verbatim.","start":3041.619,"stop":3073.98,"duration":32.36},{"text":"But the Deputy District Attorney said, well, I would concede that that is what your client told you.","start":3073.98,"stop":3079.686,"duration":5.71},{"text":"I won't necessarily assume that that is actually the case and as I recall the record, it was just left at that.","start":3079.686,"stop":3088.827,"duration":9.14},{"text":"As I say, there was no voir dire testimony by Gilbert himself that he had refused to be taken from his cell to go to the lineup.","start":3088.827,"stop":3098.484,"duration":9.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- I assume, there can be no doubt, can't it, that if a person doesn't know another -- wants to help identify him by his voice, that requiring this man to talk in his presence would be testimonial, could there be any doubt about that?","start":3098.484,"stop":3124.929,"duration":26.45}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would submit that if he is not saying anything incriminating --","start":3124.929,"stop":3131.778,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's --","start":3131.778,"stop":3131.805,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to be used against him --","start":3131.805,"stop":3132.484,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"He is --","start":3132.484,"stop":3132.707,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the trial --","start":3132.707,"stop":3133.541,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"He's incriminated himself by using his voice.","start":3133.541,"stop":3137.312,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, true Your Honor.","start":3137.312,"stop":3138.401,"duration":1.09},{"text":"But is voice really anymore than an essential physical characteristic, is anymore let us say then a facial expression generally or the way a person walks, moves about, when --","start":3138.401,"stop":3153.368,"duration":14.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a facial expression or a shake of the head or a nod in the head can be the same as a confession in a long words, can't it?","start":3153.368,"stop":3164.866,"duration":11.5},{"text":"Just --","start":3164.866,"stop":3165.019,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":3165.019,"stop":3165.133,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the fact that a motion can be a confession or tend in that direction.","start":3165.133,"stop":3171.338,"duration":6.21},{"text":"Your answer to that point as I gather is that he did not raise that on the voir dire.","start":3171.338,"stop":3177.698,"duration":6.36},{"text":"You know he may (Voice Overlap) --","start":3177.698,"stop":3177.85,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he did not --","start":3177.85,"stop":3178.202,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of one of your answers.","start":3178.202,"stop":3179.867,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"That is one of our answers and he did not come -- claim on voir dire that there was any violation of his privilege against self-incrimination.","start":3179.867,"stop":3190.27,"duration":10.4},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3190.27,"stop":3192.21,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask this one more question, does the California procedure permit the defendant in such circumstances to have a voir dire examination or a hearing on the question of the propriety of the lineup or must he do that in that trial on guilt or innocence?","start":3192.21,"stop":3222.013,"duration":29.8}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he -- I would say that he could certainly do it during the trial.","start":3222.013,"stop":3228.563,"duration":6.55},{"text":"In fact in this case, there was some voir dire on the part of Gilbert himself relative to the voluntariness of the giving of the handwriting exemplars so, I would say he could certainly do it then.","start":3228.563,"stop":3242.986,"duration":14.42},{"text":"I -- whether he -- of course he can bring a -- make a pretrial motion to suppress on search and seizure grounds, perhaps it could be extended to this situation too, but the point that I was stressing is that there -- appears to have been no indication that such was desired in this case.","start":3242.986,"stop":3268.683,"duration":25.7}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But could we say that as a matter of California practice, his counsel would know that he had a right to bring this up on a pretrial motion or on the other hand that he's entitled to rely on the fact that all he could do would be to test the credibility of the witnesses on the trial.","start":3268.683,"stop":3295.895,"duration":27.21}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't know if there's any California law precisely on the subject, but I would certainly say that he could do it at the trial.","start":3295.895,"stop":3305.696,"duration":9.8},{"text":"In fact, there was some just -- in this colloquy that I was referring to between counsels.","start":3305.696,"stop":3309.571,"duration":3.88},{"text":"There were some that was referenced by defense counsel that well, maybe we might be able to find the marshal and bring him in to testify, in other words, by voir dire, there were certainly no indication that they couldn't have -- I would say that if Gilbert or U.S. Marshal had been found that the -- they could've had some voir dire there.","start":3309.571,"stop":3329.94,"duration":20.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would think that that might be important if you rely on the fact that the -- that they're not entitled to any relief because counsel didn't raised this on voir dire.","start":3329.94,"stop":3343.997,"duration":14.06},{"text":"Now if it is the practice and the Court recognized it, that these things must be brought up in that manner or they are considered waived as one thing, but if there is no law in California and if normally, all they're entitled to is to test the credibility of witnesses on the trial itself, you would have your -- have a different situation and your defense on that regard wouldn't be so strong, would it?","start":3343.997,"stop":3370.249,"duration":26.25}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps not if the -- would just be my impression that certainly the defense could bring such a motion and I don't -- couldn't guarantee that the trial court would necessarily entertain it before the trial but I think the court certainly would consider it during the trial.","start":3370.249,"stop":3390.871,"duration":20.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3390.871,"stop":3391.824,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Very well.","start":3391.824,"stop":3392.049,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Norman H. Sokolow","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3392.049,"stop":3397.906,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. James, we've taken so much of your time -- of your colleague that the -- your time is almost up.","start":3397.906,"stop":3403.614,"duration":5.71},{"text":"But I'll you 10 more minutes in which to complete your argument.","start":3403.614,"stop":3409.463,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":3409.463,"stop":3410.71,"duration":1.25},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":3410.71,"stop":3413.132,"duration":2.42},{"text":"The time remaining to respond, I will discuss the first point that it was brought up by counsel for the petitioner and that was whether the admission of the statements of the co-defendant King, with limiting instructions which statements implicated the defendant Gilbert, violated his right and denied him a fair trial.","start":3413.132,"stop":3435.619,"duration":22.49},{"text":"It is our position of course that under the limiting instructions that there was no denial of a fair trial and that the jury could follow these instructions and it was not that type of a case that they were unable to --","start":3435.619,"stop":3447.903,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Did this happen at the federal trial?","start":3447.903,"stop":3451.031,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Not that I know of, Your Honor.","start":3451.031,"stop":3453.13,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue was (Voice Overlap) --","start":3453.13,"stop":3453.972,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was no issue raised in the federal case.","start":3453.972,"stop":3455.962,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3455.962,"stop":3457.937,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3457.937,"stop":3458.605,"duration":0.67},{"text":"King wasn't involved in those robberies.","start":3458.605,"stop":3461.805,"duration":3.2},{"text":"They were separate robberies.","start":3461.805,"stop":3463.553,"duration":1.75},{"text":"King was only involved in the robbery involving Mutual Savings of Alhambra, and so it -- wasn't involved in that case.","start":3463.553,"stop":3470.538,"duration":6.99},{"text":"It is our position that this case does not bring -- present an occasion where this Court might want to reexamine the holding that it made in Delli Paoli.","start":3470.538,"stop":3481.213,"duration":10.68},{"text":"We think that the circumstances here quite clearly point out that the jury in this case was able to follow the limiting instructions and we want to emphasize the fact that these limiting instructions were very precise.","start":3481.213,"stop":3494.834,"duration":13.62},{"text":"They were given, not at only at the end of the case, but the admonitions were given to the jury at the very time the statements were being introduced.","start":3494.834,"stop":3502.702,"duration":7.87},{"text":"I think the five factors, which this Court found very important, Delli Paoli apply here, and that this is even a stronger case than Delli Paoli.","start":3502.702,"stop":3512.613,"duration":9.91},{"text":"There are certain considerations that we should note here.","start":3512.613,"stop":3515.34,"duration":2.73},{"text":"In this case, the two defendants were represented by separate attorneys.","start":3515.34,"stop":3520.077,"duration":4.74},{"text":"In fact that there was a separability as to them was made evident to them through out the case.","start":3520.077,"stop":3526.263,"duration":6.19},{"text":"The defendants were represented as they say by separate counsel and there was no motion needed, pretrial or during the trial for a separate trial and we think this is significant as the case developed.","start":3526.263,"stop":3541.291,"duration":15.03},{"text":"It is also to be noted that the co-defendant King took the stand and on examination on the stand acknowledged that his statements were motivated by desire, to place the (Inaudible) Gilbert, and to point the finger of guilt at him.","start":3541.291,"stop":3557.186,"duration":15.89},{"text":"And the district attorney didn't rely on this statement as to Gilbert, in fact he was discounting the statements of King and discounting particularly that part of it which would indicate that there was compulsion on the part of King because of Gilbert's actions and the like.","start":3557.186,"stop":3575.279,"duration":18.09},{"text":"But we think that these are all significant factors which would show that there was no unfairness in the introduction into this joint trial of the statements of a co-defendant with these very clear and explicit limiting instructions.","start":3575.279,"stop":3590.43,"duration":15.15},{"text":"Now, Mr. Sokolow has briefly touched upon the circumstances of the crime.","start":3590.43,"stop":3596.108,"duration":5.68},{"text":"The statement of King to the authorities was that he and the co-defendant, Weaver, the co-robber I should say, Weaver who was killed in this robbery had met at a parole meeting and thereafter, they had discussed the stealing of the car by King for certain purposes.","start":3596.108,"stop":3614.884,"duration":18.78},{"text":"And it was agreed on the morning of January the 3rd 1964 that King would steal a car.","start":3614.884,"stop":3620.765,"duration":5.88},{"text":"He stole one.","start":3620.765,"stop":3621.532,"duration":0.77},{"text":"He met Weaver and Gilbert.","start":3621.532,"stop":3623.731,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Drove with them up through Alhambra and awaited for them out there.","start":3623.731,"stop":3626.89,"duration":3.16},{"text":"His statement to the officer was they returned -- Weaver was bleeding profusely and King -- Gilbert, according to King's statement, put a gun up to his stomach and told me, he'd better do what he told him to do, and that he had just killed a cop and he'd probably kill more that day.","start":3626.89,"stop":3645.035,"duration":18.14},{"text":"And King went with Gilbert to Gilbert's apartment where apparently Gilbert made another attempt on his life according to King's statements.","start":3645.035,"stop":3654.235,"duration":9.2},{"text":"But thereafter, King admitted that Gilbert gave him $1300 and King drove Gilbert to a place where he met someone and King left.","start":3654.235,"stop":3663.274,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Now this was a purport of King's statements.","start":3663.274,"stop":3666.49,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Now, King took the stand and testified insofar as it was immaterial to the charges, the same as his statement.","start":3666.49,"stop":3674.333,"duration":7.84},{"text":"He omitted in his testimony the reference to the statements supposedly made by Gilbert that he just shot a cop and that he would kill more.","start":3674.333,"stop":3683.497,"duration":9.16},{"text":"Now, we submit that under the circumstances of this case, when the statement was introduced with limiting instructions and I think it is significant at this time to note that at the penalty phase of a trial, these statements were not reintroduced and that there was no testimony by King at the penalty phase and the district attorney made no comment on the statements of the defendant King.","start":3683.497,"stop":3710.314,"duration":26.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it the same jury though that tried both?","start":3710.314,"stop":3712.75,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, under one -- Penal Code Section 190.1, in the ordinary case, unless there is some unusual circumstance, the jury that adheres the determination of guilt or innocence will also determine a penalty.","start":3712.75,"stop":3724.732,"duration":11.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3724.732,"stop":3724.966,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"And at the penalty trial, as to the guilt or innocence of the defendant has been determined, the jury can hear -- the testimony concerning the circumstances of the crime, the background and history of the defendant and any evidence in aggravation or mitigation of a penalty.","start":3724.966,"stop":3740.329,"duration":15.36},{"text":"We submit that at that time, the people's testimony related to the background and history of this defendant Gilbert just starting out with a murder he committed when he was serving time in a state prison in 1947, a burglary that he committed in 1960, when he was -- after he was paroled.","start":3740.329,"stop":3759.174,"duration":18.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That is Gilbert?","start":3759.174,"stop":3760.089,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"This was Gilbert.","start":3760.089,"stop":3760.999,"duration":0.91},{"text":"The escape in 1963 and then the series of robberies that he started in October of 1963 culminating in these acts of violence that occurred on January 3rd of 1964.","start":3760.999,"stop":3772.896,"duration":11.9},{"text":"And this is what the jury heard in determining the penalty and we don't understand this case as being a challenge to the constitutionality of Penal Code Section 190.1.","start":3772.896,"stop":3784.518,"duration":11.62},{"text":"And we submit that there was no unfairness in the penalty trial where a guilt or innocence of the defendant Gilbert having already been determined and that -- at the guilt trial, there was obviously no prejudice because there were limiting instructions and I think there were five factors in Delli Paoli which this Court dealt with very significant which we feel exist in this case.","start":3784.518,"stop":3810.557,"duration":26.04},{"text":"My first note as I'd already indicated that the judge in this case wasn't content with just merely giving an instruction at the end of the case, telling the jury that the statements of a co-defendant made in -- not in the presence of the other defendant wasn't binding on it.","start":3810.557,"stop":3825.794,"duration":15.24},{"text":"At the very time the statement was made and this was at the close of the People's case in chief, the counsel then representing Gilbert, when a question was asked of Officer Bennett concerning King's statements, said I will object to the question Your Honor as to the defendant Gilbert on the ground that it is hearsay as to him.","start":3825.794,"stop":3844.685,"duration":18.89},{"text":"And the district attorney then said, the objection is well taken.","start":3844.685,"stop":3847.656,"duration":2.97},{"text":"And the Court said, obviously, it wouldn't apply to the defendant Gilbert and whatever is said here, you are to draw absolutely no connection with the defendant Gilbert and disregarded insofar as the defendant Gilbert is concerned.","start":3847.656,"stop":3860.042,"duration":12.39},{"text":"Now, thereafter, counsel representing Gilbert made a motion that the references to Gilbert be deleted in this statement and the Court heard this and determined that it wouldn't be feasible to delete these references by name to Gilbert and of -- obviously of course at that time, at the end of the People's case, with all this eyewitness identification, the identity of the particular person namely Gilbert was clear and the Court felt that it would not be fair for the declarant to delete it.","start":3860.042,"stop":3889.525,"duration":29.48},{"text":"However, it continued.","start":3889.525,"stop":3891.378,"duration":1.85},{"text":"I think however at this time in view of the testimony of this witness, which she has not completed as yet that I should inform you that this testimony is not binding on the defendant Gilbert in anyway.","start":3891.378,"stop":3901.768,"duration":10.39},{"text":"It is completely hearsay as far as he is concerned, you are not to draw any inferences whatever from the testimony you've heard from this witness as to anything in connection with the defendant Gilbert.","start":3901.768,"stop":3911.7,"duration":9.93},{"text":"I will warn you again about this, but I thought it would only be fair that I give you this admonition.","start":3911.7,"stop":3916.343,"duration":4.64},{"text":"And the Court continued to warn constantly during the introduction of the statements and it concluded with the instruction given both at the guilt phase and at the penalty phase, that they were not to consider the statements of the co-defendant made outside of the presence.","start":3916.343,"stop":3932.517,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Now, we submit that this was a very significant factor.","start":3932.517,"stop":3938.672,"duration":6.16},{"text":"We would urge that in Delli Paoli, this Court found that the fact that -- in that case the conspiracy was a simple one was -- and therefore the instruction would be easy for the jury to understand was an important factor.","start":3938.672,"stop":3951.518,"duration":12.85},{"text":"We submit that the case, the issues here was simple and that the severability as to the two defendants was significant.","start":3951.518,"stop":3959.463,"duration":7.95},{"text":"Gilbert was the one who entered the Savings and Loan, shot the police officer.","start":3959.463,"stop":3963.922,"duration":4.46},{"text":"King's position was merely the driver of the get-away car.","start":3963.922,"stop":3967.773,"duration":3.85},{"text":"We also note that there were separate attorneys and we've also mentioned there was no request at anytime for a separate trial as to these two defendants.","start":3967.773,"stop":3976.482,"duration":8.71},{"text":"Now, the introduction of the statement of King was postponed to the end of the Government's case and this Court felt that that was significant in Delli Paoli because it made the instructions in the admonitions easier for the jury to understand and to apply.","start":3976.482,"stop":3990.923,"duration":14.44},{"text":"And the statement of the co-defendant in Delli Paoli merely corroborated what was already in the Governor's -- Government's case and we submit that at this stage, the jury obviously knew that Gilbert was the man who perpetrated the robbery for all the mass of eyewitness identification.","start":3990.923,"stop":4008.204,"duration":17.28},{"text":"And they had the confrontation in Gilbert which they didn't have in Delli Paoli as I recall.","start":4008.204,"stop":4013.51,"duration":5.31},{"text":"And I think the fifth factor which is most important is that there was nothing in the record to show that the jury was unable to understand the admonition and the instruction of the judge.","start":4013.51,"stop":4024.191,"duration":10.68},{"text":"And we think this is significant here, what is probably more significant is there is nothing in the record to show that they did not follow the admonition and the instruction of the judge.","start":4024.191,"stop":4034.052,"duration":9.86},{"text":"And I think the reference to Jackson versus Denno which counsel made is inappropriate because their witness, the Court was dealing with an involuntary confession.","start":4034.052,"stop":4043.132,"duration":9.08},{"text":"It didn't have an involuntary confession here, you had a confession that was voluntarily made by the co-defendant.","start":4043.132,"stop":4049.372,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And we submit that in -- under such a circumstance, that the rationale of this Court in Jackson wasn't applicable and what this Court said in the very recent case of Spencer versus Texas, I think it's quite appropriate where an effort was made to say that a jury could not understand it clear and explicit instruction to -- in Spencer, limit its application as to testimony concerning the defendant's prior felony convictions.","start":4049.372,"stop":4075.974,"duration":26.6},{"text":"And this Court said, it would be extravagant in the extreme to take Jackson as it -- evidencing a general distrust on the part of this Court, of the ability of juries to approach their test responsibly and to sort out issues given to them under proper instructions by the judge in the criminal case or standing for the proposition that limiting instructions can never purge the erroneous introduction of evidence or limit the evidence to its rightful purpose.","start":4075.974,"stop":4102.424,"duration":26.45},{"text":"We submit that the instructions in this case and the admonitions in this case certainly could lead the jury to limit the application of the statements of the co-defendant King and that there was no prejudice.","start":4102.424,"stop":4115.053,"duration":12.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How long was the jury (Inaudible)?","start":4115.053,"stop":4118.657,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't recall right off and of course, there were two defendants and there were seven counts of felony and I would have to make reference to the clerk's transcript for that period of time.","start":4118.657,"stop":4130.734,"duration":12.08},{"text":"I don't think it was any unusual period of time.","start":4130.734,"stop":4133.999,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any deliberation that they asked him for supplementary instruction?","start":4133.999,"stop":4137.937,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they came back and they asked for instructions.","start":4137.937,"stop":4141.653,"duration":3.72},{"text":"They asked for the reading of the testimony, I believe, of one of the defense witnesses, they asked for instructions as it related to accomplices and to corroboration as I recall.","start":4141.653,"stop":4152.676,"duration":11.02},{"text":"They did not ask for the repetition of any instructions relating to what they should do or how they should treat statements of a co-defendant.","start":4152.676,"stop":4161.139,"duration":8.46},{"text":"And I think those instructions were clear and as this Court pointed in Delli Paoli explicitly.","start":4161.139,"stop":4167.517,"duration":6.38},{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":4167.517,"stop":4167.706,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. James, what was the --","start":4167.706,"stop":4168.687,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4168.687,"stop":4169.471,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the precise reason the Court gave for setting aside the conviction of King?","start":4169.471,"stop":4180.733,"duration":11.26}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason for the -- in the California Supreme Court --","start":4180.733,"stop":4183.923,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4183.923,"stop":4183.969,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was their application of the Dorado rule, that the record did not show that there had been an admonition request -- required People versus Dorado with which this Court is familiar, that the defendant could have an attorney and that he had a right to remain silent.","start":4183.969,"stop":4199.489,"duration":15.52},{"text":"Now, this was of course prior to June 13th of last year and we now know that it was not a federally compelled reversal.","start":4199.489,"stop":4210.83,"duration":11.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if that confession could not be used against King, and the man who gave it and he was granted a new trial because of that.","start":4210.83,"stop":4223.691,"duration":12.86},{"text":"Why does the state insist that it ought to -- it could be used to whatever extent?","start":4223.691,"stop":4229.321,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The jury might have used it as against the man who is his co-defendant.","start":4229.321,"stop":4236.642,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"By the man whose the -- King's co-defendant, the declarant's co-defendant?","start":4236.642,"stop":4239.641,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4239.641,"stop":4239.962,"duration":0.32},{"text":"Gilbert.","start":4239.962,"stop":4240.69,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Gilbert, well the --","start":4240.69,"stop":4241.658,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Why did they --","start":4241.658,"stop":4241.959,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"The state --","start":4241.959,"stop":4242.842,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you take the position as the man who gave it was entitled to have a new trial because it wasn't properly obtained and yet they used it against the man concerning whom the judge had said it was hearsay?","start":4242.842,"stop":4258.172,"duration":15.33}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the Court felt that the jury could follow the instructions in the admonition of the Court and not apply the statement made by the co-defendant with these limiting instructions to Gilbert.","start":4258.172,"stop":4269.609,"duration":11.44},{"text":"And that --","start":4269.609,"stop":4269.838,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if it (Voice Overlap) --","start":4269.838,"stop":4270.016,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it had no prejudice.","start":4270.016,"stop":4270.785,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But if bad against one, why wouldn't it have been bad against both?","start":4270.785,"stop":4273.971,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it was not introduced this to Gilbert.","start":4273.971,"stop":4276.803,"duration":2.83},{"text":"And the Court specifically admonished the jury that it was not to be introduced as to Gilbert and they were not to consider it or draw any inferences from that testimony as it related to Gilbert.","start":4276.803,"stop":4287.58,"duration":10.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you have told that -- you take that it was not prejudicial against this man largely because King took a stand and testified frankly the same thing, didn't you?","start":4287.58,"stop":4301.606,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the --","start":4301.606,"stop":4302.327,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4302.327,"stop":4303.208,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Gilbert certainly had confrontation which as I recall in Delli Paoli.","start":4303.208,"stop":4307.115,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4307.115,"stop":4307.363,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"The Delli Paoli did not have confrontation of the co-defendant Whitley who didn't take the stand.","start":4307.363,"stop":4312.629,"duration":5.27},{"text":"So one of the --","start":4312.629,"stop":4313.378,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":4313.378,"stop":4313.531,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- big objections to the introduction of hearsay was obviated confrontation and the right of cross-examination under oath.","start":4313.531,"stop":4320.519,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does that lead you to the harmless error rule?","start":4320.519,"stop":4323.863,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, if we believe that juries can follow simple and explicit instructions, we would find that there was no error here because the jury was told expressly not to consider this testimony as it related to Gilbert.","start":4323.863,"stop":4338.069,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But I wonder if --","start":4338.069,"stop":4338.192,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"And it had some --","start":4338.192,"stop":4339.36,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I wonder if -- whether you use the testimony that King gave in the courtroom against Gilbert, and as a result, you come out with harmless error, why wouldn't that same testimony that King gave against himself in the courtroom accomplished the same result?","start":4339.36,"stop":4360.262,"duration":20.9}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"That wasn't the basis for the reversal.","start":4360.262,"stop":4362.306,"duration":2.04},{"text":"It was not because King took the stand and testified himself.","start":4362.306,"stop":4366.38,"duration":4.07},{"text":"That had no relation --","start":4366.38,"stop":4367.014,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4367.014,"stop":4367.331,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- with the reversal in King --","start":4367.331,"stop":4368.182,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Why was that?","start":4368.182,"stop":4368.549,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because of the introduction --","start":4368.549,"stop":4369.572,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4369.572,"stop":4369.956,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of those statements in confession.","start":4369.956,"stop":4371.3,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But, if he took the stand and frankly confessed his guilt, well, wouldn't it be just as much harmless error in that situation as it would as against this defendant?","start":4371.3,"stop":4387.151,"duration":15.85}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think however the California Supreme Court, when applied to harmless error rule where the -- its interpretation of the Dorado was involved.","start":4387.151,"stop":4395.386,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":4395.386,"stop":4396.454,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":4396.454,"stop":4396.632,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":4396.632,"stop":4397.16,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. James, I looked at the fact mentioned by Mr. Sokolow, I mean, I don't (Inaudible) I have the wrong pages.","start":4397.16,"stop":4405.264,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, incidentally, I understand the Court only has one copy of the record.","start":4405.264,"stop":4411.117,"duration":5.85},{"text":"We would be very happy to lodge with the Court our copies of the record and while we only have --","start":4411.117,"stop":4418.112,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought maybe you had a better page.","start":4418.112,"stop":4420.585,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe so, I'll ask Mr. Sokolow (Voice Overlap) about it.","start":4420.585,"stop":4421.655,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose we would agree about it, will you do that (Voice Overlap) --","start":4421.655,"stop":4423.179,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll do that by letter?","start":4423.179,"stop":4424.431,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4424.431,"stop":4424.725,"duration":0.29},{"text":"Will you -- would you just leave with the clerk please.","start":4424.725,"stop":4426.48,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I understand what Mr. Justice Clark and I'm concerned with this too.","start":4426.48,"stop":4429.984,"duration":3.5},{"text":"We looked at this record at page numbers to which Mr. Sokolow referred as bearing on what occurred at the lineup and the pages do not bear on what occurs at the lineup --","start":4429.984,"stop":4441.182,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"We --","start":4441.182,"stop":4441.257,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"One of them was whether the respective juror believes in capital punishment, and the other similar sort of case.","start":4441.257,"stop":4448.424,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"So long for that --","start":4448.424,"stop":4450.102,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"That's probably the one -- Volume 1 of the voir dire of the jury.","start":4450.102,"stop":4453.552,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"One, the second volume?","start":4453.552,"stop":4455.728,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's the preliminary volume to that, as I understand it.","start":4455.728,"stop":4459.436,"duration":3.71},{"text":"It's a very thin volume of the transcript.","start":4459.436,"stop":4462.122,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you just refer us to the Volume and the page where there is any evidence referring on what occurred at the lineup.","start":4462.122,"stop":4468.406,"duration":6.28},{"text":"That's what I'd like.","start":4468.406,"stop":4468.481,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"William E. James","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we -- we'll lodge you our copy of that transcript with the Court and the pages.","start":4468.481,"stop":4474.801,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Thank you Your Honors.","start":4474.801,"stop":4475.571,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":4475.571,"stop":4477.878,"duration":2.31},{"text":"Mr. McKissack.","start":4477.878,"stop":4479.005,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor, may it please the Court.","start":4479.005,"stop":4480.31,"duration":1.31},{"text":"In the time remaining, I wish to direct my attention to two issues and two issues alone, one being Jackson versus Denno and the Delli Paoli controversy, and secondly the question at the lineup.","start":4480.31,"stop":4488.953,"duration":8.64},{"text":"But first, let me say that on this question of Delli Paoli or Jackson versus Denno, we must bear in mind that we have the same jury adjudicating both the question of depth and the question of the merits, that is guilt or innocence, and all they did was take -- I think a week in before they started on the other matter.","start":4488.953,"stop":4503.608,"duration":14.65},{"text":"In other words, when the verdict came in, I think it was perhaps a day or so, and then they immediately began to deliberate it.","start":4503.608,"stop":4508.902,"duration":5.29},{"text":"And I think its mere folly to assume that after weeks and weeks and weeks of trial that they're suddenly going to forget all the evidence they've heard.","start":4508.902,"stop":4515.742,"duration":6.84},{"text":"And merely because King did not testified again on the death penalty question that there -- to have forgotten what they have previously heard.","start":4515.742,"stop":4522.483,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Were they important points made in the confession that King did not make on the stand?","start":4522.483,"stop":4528.223,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and the California Supreme Court points this out quite well in its opinion.","start":4528.223,"stop":4532.075,"duration":3.85},{"text":"The California Supreme Court points out that amongst other things, that it's not going to -- as to reverse this as to King, because it has in mind the fact that his testimony in Court is not nearly so damaging as his testimony out of Court.","start":4532.075,"stop":4545.273,"duration":13.2},{"text":"For example, the statements about Gilbert, killing a cop and going to kill more, and the statements about Gilbert then threatening the King -- kill King, but his efforts being ineffectual, none of this was in the testimony of King.","start":4545.273,"stop":4555.19,"duration":9.92},{"text":"It was only in the hearsay recitations, given by King to the officer.","start":4555.19,"stop":4558.863,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Which came first?","start":4558.863,"stop":4560.254,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"The recitations came first.","start":4560.254,"stop":4562.096,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Then King, after that took the stand in the California --","start":4562.096,"stop":4563.989,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but not -- opportunity to cross-examine him with respect to his previous confession or statements that he made previously in addition to what he testified to?","start":4563.989,"stop":4576.963,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"As to defense counsel, I -- as I remember, defense counsel attempted to do this.","start":4576.963,"stop":4581.147,"duration":4.18},{"text":"I know the point was made in the state briefs that one of the things he could not do is to go into this prior confession and therefore he held that -- he felt that that this was an error in itself.","start":4581.147,"stop":4591.456,"duration":10.31},{"text":"I mean, there's an opportunity to cross-examine him since that King took the stand, yes.","start":4591.456,"stop":4595.94,"duration":4.48},{"text":"But --","start":4595.94,"stop":4596.739,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this wasn't in evidence against the petitioner here.","start":4596.739,"stop":4603.398,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't in evidence against the petitioner and I can't imagine in front of the jury how defense counsel would to -- would dare to ask King on the stand questions that would just reiterate that which the jury has been instructed to forget.","start":4603.398,"stop":4615.062,"duration":11.66},{"text":"I think it would be quite deleterious even of he had right in the world to do it.","start":4615.062,"stop":4618.972,"duration":3.91},{"text":"I can't imagine anyone doing it.","start":4618.972,"stop":4620.599,"duration":1.63},{"text":"It wouldn't make much sense, I don't think.","start":4620.599,"stop":4622.747,"duration":2.15},{"text":"But, the death penalty question in California, there's no reasonable doubt standard even.","start":4622.747,"stop":4627.085,"duration":4.34},{"text":"It's thrown entirely in the lap of the jury.","start":4627.085,"stop":4628.945,"duration":1.86},{"text":"There is no way to determine now what factors influenced them and what factors didn't.","start":4628.945,"stop":4633.199,"duration":4.25},{"text":"And in this case, I would suggest, when a man's life is at stake, that one of the most crucial questions is what are the chances that's he's going to repeat this kind of conduct, how confirmed a criminal is he, are there any hope for rehabilitation.","start":4633.199,"stop":4646.231,"duration":13.03},{"text":"And when this statement had came in, designating him as a cop killer by his own admission, and saying that he's going to kill more, and the jury couldn't forget that no matter how clearly they were told to disregard it.","start":4646.231,"stop":4657.819,"duration":11.59},{"text":"I would point out it would just be absolutely impossible for the jury to follow the instruction under those circumstances.","start":4657.819,"stop":4663.574,"duration":5.75},{"text":"Furthermore, as to that particular statement, if we go back to Delli Paoli, I don't see what the admissibility is, in other words, in what way is it admissible against King because he's -- recites the fact that Gilbert said that he'd killed one policeman and he's going to kill someone else.","start":4663.574,"stop":4678.263,"duration":14.69},{"text":"I suggest, this is merely the backdoor technique that by use of the -- what would ordinarily be admissions against King of bringing in something which doesn't even qualify with that score and that it radiates over against Gilbert, and no instruction can cure it.","start":4678.263,"stop":4690.317,"duration":12.05},{"text":"So I think insofar as the --","start":4690.317,"stop":4691.731,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree with your adversary statement that there was no motion for a -- either a mistrial or a separate trial at any stage in -- when this -- a bit -- and particularly, when the confession was introduced with the (Voice Overlap) --","start":4691.731,"stop":4706.289,"duration":14.56}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- on my recollection is that there was a motion for mistrial, but I could be mistaken.","start":4706.289,"stop":4709.716,"duration":3.43},{"text":"There was no motion for severance.","start":4709.716,"stop":4711.872,"duration":2.16},{"text":"And my commentary on this would be that the People versus Aranda rule in California did not come down until after Gilbert had been tried.","start":4711.872,"stop":4718.597,"duration":6.72},{"text":"And the -- that's upon other opinions by this Court and other courts have indicated that counsel can't be expected to anticipate the law -- changes in the law.","start":4718.597,"stop":4726.487,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And I would point out that -- if this Court does adopt an Aranda like rule, that the Government should be charged with letting the opposition know, if they have these kind of statements and they're going to introduce them, because after all, it's the Government that brings the joint trial rather than two separate trials because the Government knows this facts and knows whether they need these statements and whether they are going to be introduced.","start":4726.487,"stop":4747.609,"duration":21.12},{"text":"Defense counsel would have to resort merely to surmise.","start":4747.609,"stop":4750.262,"duration":2.65},{"text":"So I feel Your Honor that that -- there's certainly was no harmless error even if that standard be applied.","start":4750.262,"stop":4753.865,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- there's nothing in the record to indicate that Gilbert's counsel moved that there had been a confession by King?","start":4753.865,"stop":4759.981,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely not.","start":4759.981,"stop":4762.557,"duration":2.58},{"text":"On the question of the lineup --","start":4762.557,"stop":4763.762,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand that the Aranda rule is, in circumstances like this, an advance of trial, the prosecution is under duty to advise the defense of the existence of the statement of --","start":4763.762,"stop":4774.279,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":4774.279,"stop":4774.929,"duration":0.65},{"text":"I insinuated that, I didn't mean to.","start":4774.929,"stop":4776.706,"duration":1.78},{"text":"I was advocating that that should be the position of the Court --","start":4776.706,"stop":4779.238,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What I -- no, no, no, I'd say what is the Aranda rule?","start":4779.238,"stop":4781.283,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"The Aranda rule says, that where you have this kind of a situation -- it doesn't really talk about whose duty it is to tell who and what.","start":4781.283,"stop":4788.49,"duration":7.21},{"text":"Perhaps, it's implicit that the defendant wouldn't then make a motion for severance.","start":4788.49,"stop":4792.279,"duration":3.79},{"text":"But of course, it's saying to counsel in future cases, you can make a motion for severance and here's what to do.","start":4792.279,"stop":4797.21,"duration":4.93},{"text":"Counsel should make a motion for severance if you have these kinds of statements.","start":4797.21,"stop":4801.249,"duration":4.04},{"text":"And then the prosecution would have the opportunity of offering an alternative --","start":4801.249,"stop":4803.77,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":4803.77,"stop":4805.275,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of effective deletions.","start":4805.275,"stop":4806.811,"duration":1.54},{"text":"This could be done by a joint --","start":4806.811,"stop":4808.122,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know but, how was the defense learned that there were such a statement as King?","start":4808.122,"stop":4812.494,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not (Inaudible).","start":4812.494,"stop":4814.982,"duration":2.49},{"text":"As a matter of policy in California, each defendant has a separate arrest report and the -- in some places, the co-defense counsel might know what the other person has said, in other cases, they might not.","start":4814.982,"stop":4824.931,"duration":9.95},{"text":"On the issue of the lineup, I just wished to point -- bring a point to the Court's attention.","start":4824.931,"stop":4830.181,"duration":5.25},{"text":"One other paragraph from the federal court opinion, its right after the one that Mr. Justice Brennan quoted where witnesses from all four robberies were assembled in the audience, after each prisoner went to the general routine, the FBI agent in-charged asked if the witnesses wished to see any of the prisoners again.","start":4830.181,"stop":4845.961,"duration":15.78},{"text":"The witnesses who were -- witnesses were instructed to call out the numbers of any prisoner they recognized and they told that if they had doubts, this was the time to see the prisoners the second time and asked them to repeat phrases used in their respective robberies.","start":4845.961,"stop":4857.445,"duration":11.48},{"text":"The witnesses called out the numbers of two or three of the prisoners including appellant, that's Gilbert, many of them calling out appellant's number.","start":4857.445,"stop":4863.329,"duration":5.88},{"text":"The prisoner does select and were asked by various witnesses to give -- to repeat given phrases, walk in a particular way, try on particular articles of clothing.","start":4863.329,"stop":4871.228,"duration":7.9},{"text":"The appellant was asked to speak loudly, to walk rapidly and slowly while repeating certain phrases, and to speak more loudly which one witness testified appellant refused to do and to put on a hat which of two of the witnesses testified, at first they refused to do.","start":4871.228,"stop":4883.989,"duration":12.76},{"text":"The witnesses talked amongst themselves as the lineup progressed.","start":4883.989,"stop":4887.039,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Now I think this bears on --","start":4887.039,"stop":4887.621,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What the --","start":4887.621,"stop":4888.245,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- why counsel --","start":4888.245,"stop":4889.029,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you reading from?","start":4889.029,"stop":4890.285,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"From the dissenting opinion of Justice Browning recounting the facts as they occurred at this lineup as if -- upon the appellate -- from the --","start":4890.285,"stop":4898.513,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask, as I understand it -- did I understand Mr. James to say that this federal trial --","start":4898.513,"stop":4903.965,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4903.965,"stop":4904.098,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was for a different robbery from the verdict trial, that -- from the robbery involving a murder trial?","start":4904.098,"stop":4910.424,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4910.424,"stop":4911.251,"duration":0.83},{"text":"There were a lot of banks robbed.","start":4911.251,"stop":4912.553,"duration":1.3},{"text":"So the federal courts sees -- don't have the bank robbery, but we had basically the same evidence on the same lineup and the same witnesses involved.","start":4912.553,"stop":4919.489,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but were the inquiries at the lineup all directed to -- pinning all of these robberies on Gilbert and --","start":4919.489,"stop":4926.355,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4926.355,"stop":4927.137,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not on somebody else?","start":4927.137,"stop":4928.141,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4928.141,"stop":4928.754,"duration":0.61},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, that's an interesting point because you have a state trial for one bank robbery for which the other is really admissible.","start":4928.754,"stop":4933.984,"duration":5.23},{"text":"The same witnesses that are going to testify on that alone are in the same chamber and not segregated from other witnesses when they hear questions about numerous bank robberies.","start":4933.984,"stop":4941.754,"duration":7.77},{"text":"And they just call out numbers and then the avalanche continues.","start":4941.754,"stop":4944.828,"duration":3.07},{"text":"And I would point out that this gives repeated emphasis to the fact that counsel should be present in these kinds of predicaments mainly because its unforeseeable what can happen.","start":4944.828,"stop":4953.326,"duration":8.5},{"text":"I think the destruction of the case for the prosecution is this simple and that is if self-incriminatory situations can conceivably arise and here they have arise.","start":4953.326,"stop":4961.698,"duration":8.37},{"text":"Then we should appoint counsels so that we can protect against these things.","start":4961.698,"stop":4964.846,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Otherwise we have a retroactive determination which requires exclusion of evidence which should not happen.","start":4964.846,"stop":4970.247,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Thank you sir.","start":4970.247,"stop":4974.9,"duration":4.65}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 15, 1967","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren13/oral_argument_audio/15453","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 223, Jesse James Gilbert, Petitioner, versus California.","start":0,"stop":22.518,"duration":22.52},{"text":"Mr. McKissack.","start":22.518,"stop":23.987,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor, may it please the Court.","start":23.987,"stop":26.844,"duration":2.86},{"text":"As the Court undoubtedly knows, the certiorari was granted on four different grounds and I would propose to merely highlight what counsel estimates be the pivotal concerns in each one of these contentions which we have brought before this Court commencing first with the question of the confession by co-defendant in whether or not limiting instructions to the jury would be sufficient to eliminate any potential prejudice.","start":26.844,"stop":51.861,"duration":25.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKissack, is there any place in the papers that you filed that we have copies of the opinion, Supreme Court of California, I have it here in the California Court Second series but I wondered if -- I didn't see it in any petition for certiorari or record or anywhere else?","start":51.861,"stop":69.406,"duration":17.55}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"It was in the petition for certiorari, I'm almost positive.","start":69.406,"stop":77.379,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- don't delay.","start":77.379,"stop":78.698,"duration":1.32},{"text":"I was just interested though, and -- by I'd say, I have it --","start":78.698,"stop":81.566,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":81.566,"stop":81.936,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in this bound volume (Voice Overlap).","start":81.936,"stop":82.993,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm almost positive that it was in the petition for certiorari, but of course I could be mistaken.","start":82.993,"stop":88.199,"duration":5.21},{"text":"The first issue within be the question of a confession of the -- of a co-defendant in whether or not it could be limited to the declarant not to a non-declarant not used against him.","start":88.199,"stop":97.752,"duration":9.55},{"text":"Then, the duo counsel in Fifth Amendment questions first, the lineup issue and in the issue of handwriting exemplars and if time permits, I would then like to reach the issue of search and seizure and the comp -- and the effects of a violation if there was in fact a violation of search and seizure laws.","start":97.752,"stop":115.276,"duration":17.52},{"text":"Now, first directing my attention to the question of the confession issue and as used against the co-defendant, I would point out that I think that the reason -- array of judicial decisions and the Court's own judicial intuition would point out that this is one of the most troublesome spots of a law.","start":115.276,"stop":131.657,"duration":16.38},{"text":"If we were to single out any particular problem where limiting instructions are demonstrably insufficient, I would think it would be in the area where you have a joint trial with two defendants and in this case both on trial for their lives and we have a confession, a complete confession by one which it implicates the other man.","start":131.657,"stop":151.665,"duration":20.01},{"text":"And in this case not only implicates him but you have statements made which are brought in against only the co-defendant King here which purports to say that Gilbert admitted killing a police officer and said, before he was finished, he was going to kill some more.","start":151.665,"stop":166.617,"duration":14.95},{"text":"Further statement showing that Gilbert attempted to kill his co-defendant after the completion of the bank robbery.","start":166.617,"stop":172.893,"duration":6.28},{"text":"I think this is particularly pertinent if we view this as it is, a death penalty case against the background of California Penal Code Statute 190.1 which is erroneously printed in page 3 of our reply brief, is I think 1900 or 9090 but 190.1 which throws the death penalty versus life imprisonment issue in California completely in the lap of the jury without any kind of criteria whatsoever.","start":172.893,"stop":199.094,"duration":26.2},{"text":"They have a complete freehand to consider all factors and mitigation, all factors and aggravation and then arrive upon a decision with no reasonable doubt criteria or anything, a complete decision, a decision as to whether the man should live or die.","start":199.094,"stop":214.194,"duration":15.1},{"text":"And we have brought before the jury something that would otherwise be inadmissible if it were not to the fact that this was a joint trial.","start":214.194,"stop":221.032,"duration":6.84},{"text":"But being a joint trial, the jury heard the same jury that decided the guilt of this man and had to adjudicate or had to decide the penalty also heard the statement which set in effect that this man had killed the policeman and was going to kill more.","start":221.032,"stop":236.531,"duration":15.5},{"text":"And I can't imagine anything that could have a more devastating impact.","start":236.531,"stop":240.422,"duration":3.89},{"text":"Now, although the Aranda decision in the California Courts is merely a policy decision by the Court I feel that it hits the crux of what we got here.","start":240.422,"stop":249.265,"duration":8.84},{"text":"I feel that we have a situation that goes far beyond the yields of Jackson versus Denno because you have a situation where the jury is instructed not merely to consider the remarks of the declarant -- against the declarant, and not against the other individual.","start":249.265,"stop":267.48,"duration":18.22},{"text":"We have a situation where -- unlike in Jackson versus Denno where they have to make a preliminary determination as to whether certain evidence is admissible and then either reject it or consider it.","start":267.48,"stop":279.757,"duration":12.28},{"text":"We have a situation here where they're told to consider it and not consider it the same time.","start":279.757,"stop":284.115,"duration":4.36},{"text":"They are told to go in there and deliberate as practical men about whether or not King is telling the truth when he says that he and Weaver and Gilbert planned a bank robbery and that it was committed as King explained that it happened and then deciding whether or not that's the truth for purposes of King and then turning around under a limiting instruction in saying even though we have decided that it's true insofar as King is concerned we're to regard it as untrue insofar as Gilbert is concerned.","start":284.115,"stop":309.376,"duration":25.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKissack, Aranda was decided after this case, wasn't it?","start":309.376,"stop":312.681,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was.","start":312.681,"stop":313.71,"duration":1.03},{"text":"It was decided after the trial of this case and before the appellate decision came down.","start":313.71,"stop":318.314,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's see, decide -- Aranda was decided before the appellate decision and this case came down?","start":318.314,"stop":323.192,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, before the California Supreme Court handed down its opinion.","start":323.192,"stop":326.241,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is there any consideration of Aranda?","start":326.241,"stop":328.559,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":328.559,"stop":329.598,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":329.598,"stop":329.751,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"And the consideration of Aranda, they held that there was a violation and relied upon a lack of prejudice to affirm the conviction.","start":329.751,"stop":339.3,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case?","start":339.3,"stop":339.936,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":339.936,"stop":340.481,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":340.481,"stop":341.134,"duration":0.65},{"text":"By reason of the cautionary instruction?","start":341.134,"stop":344.512,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, by reason of the other evidence in the case.","start":344.512,"stop":347.943,"duration":3.43},{"text":"I don't think yet -- well, I should say that this, the Court did point out that the cautionary instruction was given but the heavy reliance as I read the case is upon the fact that there was eyewitness testimony by others.","start":347.943,"stop":358.964,"duration":11.02},{"text":"And to whom -- with California's approach which is I think contrary to the Fahy approach is a question of looking at the case in saying what it probably have resulted in any different decision.","start":358.964,"stop":369.082,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- and this is a harmless error question?","start":369.082,"stop":373.481,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- one way, it could be viewed that way, yes sir.","start":373.481,"stop":376.805,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the way you're presenting it, that couldn't possibly be harmless?","start":376.805,"stop":380.203,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":380.203,"stop":382.078,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Notwithstanding overwhelming additional proof of guilt?","start":382.078,"stop":386.085,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not willing to say that there could never be a case where there -- that there were not be harmed committed.","start":386.085,"stop":390.841,"duration":4.76},{"text":"But focusing upon the nearest analogous area that we have which are confession cases, this Court has held categorically throughout all the cases that have been presented, that where you have a confession involved, there's no point really inquiring into prejudice because you can't tell how much damage is concerned.","start":390.841,"stop":405.293,"duration":14.45},{"text":"Now, I'm pointing out but we not only have a confession here which mentions Gilbert 159 times, describes his role in the robbery, points out that he's a past cop killer, and he threatens to kill cops in the future.","start":405.293,"stop":415.332,"duration":10.04},{"text":"But we also have a death penalty issue, it was not a reasonable doubt standard being presented to the jury and thrown entirely in the lap of the jury as to whether this man should live or die.","start":415.332,"stop":423.934,"duration":8.6},{"text":"And obviously one of the questions is whether he is real -- to rehabilitate him.","start":423.934,"stop":428.057,"duration":4.12},{"text":"And I feel therefore that any instruction that was given and a traditional one was that you cannot consider this as to Gilbert would be completely ineffectual.","start":428.057,"stop":436.616,"duration":8.56},{"text":"And I think that it used the language of a past justice of this Court, indeed it was a peep beyond the compass of ordinary minds.","start":436.616,"stop":443.526,"duration":6.91},{"text":"I don't think that the jury could have done this.","start":443.526,"stop":448.408,"duration":4.88},{"text":"Now, of course I -- to distinguish this case from the earlier decision that we have here in Delli Paoli although I don't think this distinction need be made.","start":448.408,"stop":457.468,"duration":9.06},{"text":"In the Delli Paoli situation, there was no showing I don't think of an illegally introduced statement.","start":457.468,"stop":462.468,"duration":5},{"text":"It was a question of being legal -- legally introduced inadmissible against the man that was introduced against, but it had no right to radiate and affect the other defendant.","start":462.468,"stop":470.713,"duration":8.25},{"text":"Now, on this case so the California Supreme Court held that the statement against the declarant itself was inadmissible and therefore concluded that the only basis for having a joint trial and allowing this kind of a statement in on the grounds that if you're going to grant a joint trial and certainly there are values to it.","start":470.713,"stop":486.687,"duration":15.97},{"text":"And if you're going to say to the prosecution you can't have a joint trial then certainly the prosecution would like to get in admissions or confessions against the party that made them.","start":486.687,"stop":496.897,"duration":10.21},{"text":"You don't even have that justification because the evidence that was introduced against the co-defendant King was held to have been illegally obtained.","start":496.897,"stop":504.101,"duration":7.2},{"text":"And if --","start":504.101,"stop":504.116,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it was constitutionally -- illegally obtained?","start":504.116,"stop":507.06,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"It was held to be constitutionally --","start":507.06,"stop":508.368,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"They upheld but under the decisions of this Court, recent decisions of this Court, was that confession of the co-defendant illegally obtained?","start":508.368,"stop":518.673,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that it was Your Honor.","start":518.673,"stop":519.956,"duration":1.28},{"text":"If Your Honor is focusing upon a cutoff date question, is that what Your Honor has in mind?","start":519.956,"stop":525.243,"duration":5.29},{"text":"Well, this maybe a manner of semantics or approach, but the point would be under the test of Escobedo and all cases following from that Massiah effect, it was inadmissible.","start":525.243,"stop":535.33,"duration":10.09},{"text":"The question is, to whether Escobedo --","start":535.33,"stop":536.576,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean -- do you think these facts would satisfy Escobedo as read in Miranda?","start":536.576,"stop":544.342,"duration":7.77}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean as to the custody requirement and so forth?","start":544.342,"stop":546.522,"duration":2.18},{"text":"The --","start":546.522,"stop":547.393,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and what their counsel -- did he request counsel and was it reviewed?","start":547.393,"stop":556.043,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well no, there's a --","start":556.043,"stop":557.873,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not set of the facts -- you not satisfy Escobedo as read in Miranda, do they?","start":557.873,"stop":563.666,"duration":5.79}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"They do not -- no, they -- well, in the sense that Miranda in more and less than the cutoff question talks about the fact that because Courts differed on the interpretation of Escobedo as to whether you had to ask for a counsel or whether --","start":563.666,"stop":576.956,"duration":13.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand what -- that the California court held --","start":576.956,"stop":579.918,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":579.918,"stop":580.254,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that this was illegal -- an illegally obtained confession.","start":580.254,"stop":582.77,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":582.77,"stop":583.103,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as we're concerned, under Miranda, it's different.","start":583.103,"stop":588.688,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, after the language in Miranda, I would say that is certainly a violation but Your Honor could -- Your Honors could --","start":588.688,"stop":592.725,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But why is that a violation?","start":592.725,"stop":595.158,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of the fact that the custodial stage is attached and he had a right to an attorney at that --","start":595.158,"stop":599.208,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when did this happen?","start":599.208,"stop":601.582,"duration":2.37},{"text":"This happened before -- when did it happen?","start":601.582,"stop":605.018,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the point that I would be trying to make is that the question the Court would have to decide on this issue would be whether or not the effect of Miranda is as a constitutional ground -- alright, the violation is there but nevertheless under the Johnson case we would not apply it retroactively for the policy reason stated.","start":605.018,"stop":621.084,"duration":16.07},{"text":"But nevertheless the Court, obviously the California Court would have the right to enlarge or device its own retroactivity rule.","start":621.084,"stop":626.754,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But didn't -- didn't your California Supreme Court did so in the -- reconsidering this whole business now, you're not going with?","start":626.754,"stop":634.082,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I have it by hearsay yester -- that --","start":634.082,"stop":635.144,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it had, we (Voice Overlap) --","start":635.144,"stop":635.691,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that I heard that the day before yesterday and I have not had accessed to the opinion but this -- what I understand is in a case called People versus Rollins, California Supreme Court has unless I'm wrong applied Escobedo retroactively to the extent that it would apply to cases pending on appeal.","start":635.691,"stop":654.447,"duration":18.76},{"text":"Now, I maybe wrong but this is what the counsel who handled the case told me yesterday as I was on -- eb\\n route to the airport.","start":654.447,"stop":657.415,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But this isn't credit carrier case anyway, isn't it?","start":657.415,"stop":660.334,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":660.334,"stop":660.604,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"This isn't a credit carrier case anyway whether the (Voice Overlap) --","start":660.604,"stop":662.755,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No it is --","start":662.755,"stop":663.385,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whether this confession of his co-defendant was coerced or not.","start":663.385,"stop":667.164,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to make that a full point of contention Your Honor.","start":667.164,"stop":669.569,"duration":2.4},{"text":"I would contend it's absolutely irrelevant that this Court should not consider that a crucial factor but I was merely pointing it out because I was mindful of the fact that in the fight for Delli Paoli decision, that that factor was not present.","start":669.569,"stop":681.212,"duration":11.64},{"text":"And that in the analysis of Gilbert and Aranda, this differentiation was pointed out and I wanted to bring it to the attention of the Court for whatever bearing would have.","start":681.212,"stop":689.616,"duration":8.4},{"text":"I don't think personally that you have any bearing because I think what we're talking about here is --","start":689.616,"stop":695.448,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You say, suppose it was properly admitted against Weaver.","start":695.448,"stop":699.282,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Nevertheless, the cautionary instructions relied to 159 references as to Gilbert, the things that Weaver said Gilbert did --","start":699.282,"stop":706.741,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":706.741,"stop":707.398,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- all of those so prejudiced, whatever it maybe.","start":707.398,"stop":713.976,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Gilbert's.","start":713.976,"stop":715.008,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Gilbert's case both as to guilt or innocence, but in any event as to penalty?","start":715.008,"stop":720.104,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly as to death penalty and I think also as to guilt and innocence.","start":720.104,"stop":723.744,"duration":3.64},{"text":"That's the effect of -- that it could be either be viewed as a fact that there was too much prejudice and therefore it could be reversed under a due process standard or it could be held by analogy here that we have a confession in the case and by resort to the past confession cases, it has been pointed out that they're usually too devastating to try and to raise and that would also call for reversal.","start":723.744,"stop":749.283,"duration":25.54},{"text":"I would want -- wish to call this to the Court's attention.","start":749.283,"stop":751.325,"duration":2.04},{"text":"I think he's looking at it as a practical matter that it -- most any defense counsel would -- they concede that this is one of the most troublesome problems in the law because even though a judge and there might be a distinction here because I should bring to the attention of the Court, California has not used Aranda across the board in court trial situations.","start":751.325,"stop":768.571,"duration":17.25},{"text":"California has acknowledged that a judge for example might be able to work two hats at one time, a judge appreciates exclusionary rules.","start":768.571,"stop":775.654,"duration":7.08},{"text":"He recognizes that certain kinds of cases that there maybe overwhelming evidence but it's illegally obtained, the case goes out, the case is dismissed.","start":775.654,"stop":782.872,"duration":7.22},{"text":"But this is not something that's usually within the education and the understanding of a jury, as a matter of fact the last instruction to the jury in all California cases ends with a conclusion that their sole task is the ascertainment of the truth.","start":782.872,"stop":795.363,"duration":12.49},{"text":"And I would venture to say that when a jury goes in to the jury room this is what they have in mind and a notion of an exclusionary rule or a limiting instruction where you considered only against some and not as against others embraces a concept for you recognize that there are other purposes that may in sense collide with the total objective of total ascertainment of the truth.","start":795.363,"stop":815.257,"duration":19.89},{"text":"It may cause them to put certain things out of their mind.","start":815.257,"stop":817.961,"duration":2.7},{"text":"And I cannot imagine a more drastic situation than the one that is presented here and that is where they just can't erase it.","start":817.961,"stop":824.237,"duration":6.28},{"text":"There's just no way in the world to unring the bell and this of course is what we've pointed out.","start":824.237,"stop":828.292,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you suggest?","start":828.292,"stop":829.12,"duration":0.83},{"text":"Some kind of a general rule against the admissibility of co-defendant's confession, did they implicate the other fellow or are you saying just in a specific case like this one, it maybe that in this particular case there's an unfair trial?","start":829.12,"stop":845.202,"duration":16.08}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say first and I think in this case there was an unfair trial but I would suggest that the recent amendment to Rule 14 of the federal rules and the decision of People versus Aranda be in a sense adopted as a constitutional mandate because I think that it gropes with the problem that -- is not been wrestled with sufficiently and provides the only way out of a situation here where otherwise one man out of two is not going to get a fair trial.","start":845.202,"stop":869.781,"duration":24.58},{"text":"In connection with that, I would say that it would be the duty of the Government to raise the fact that the statements were going to be introduced so that the defendant would be on position to come back.","start":869.781,"stop":881.761,"duration":11.98},{"text":"It's the Government and not the defendant that decides on joint trials.","start":881.761,"stop":884.71,"duration":2.95},{"text":"The defendant, I'm sure Mr. Gilbert would've been quite content to go to trial by himself but because of factors and important factors that allow joint trials, he had to go to trial with a co-defendant.","start":884.71,"stop":894.217,"duration":9.51},{"text":"The Government knew this, the Government drew up the indictment, the Government issued the information against both of them jointly.","start":894.217,"stop":900.949,"duration":6.73},{"text":"The Government knew what the their evidence was, the Government knew whether they were going to introduce the confession, and therefore I would suggest that the Government should remind counsel of this, make this available to him and allow counsel the opportunity then --","start":900.949,"stop":913.519,"duration":12.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's --","start":913.519,"stop":913.534,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to make a motion for severance.","start":913.534,"stop":914.34,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this Rule 14 that you mentioned?","start":914.34,"stop":917.078,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"It's cited in the reply brief which I presented which is the blue one, cited on page 3.","start":917.078,"stop":924.736,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":924.736,"stop":925.472,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure.","start":925.472,"stop":928.165,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Basically, as I understand it it's a sort of a congressional adoption of the policies in Miranda and the recognition of the fact that he really can't have a fair trial under these circumstances.","start":928.165,"stop":939.184,"duration":11.02},{"text":"The trust of what I'm suggesting is that if we have statements that the Government says, “Alright, we're going to introduce these statements.","start":939.184,"stop":945.725,"duration":6.54},{"text":"We need these statements”.","start":945.725,"stop":947.153,"duration":1.43},{"text":"The next question for the judge to ask is, “Alright, can we delete references to the co-defendants, so satisfactorily that he will not be prejudiced”.","start":947.153,"stop":954.13,"duration":6.98},{"text":"If this can be done then of course joint trial should continue, of course the statement should be admitted.","start":954.13,"stop":958.061,"duration":3.93},{"text":"They have a value.","start":958.061,"stop":959.462,"duration":1.4},{"text":"If this cannot be done then the motion for severance should be granted so that each party has a fair trial.","start":959.462,"stop":965.664,"duration":6.2},{"text":"And this I think is an essence to the thrust of Aranda, and Aranda relies heavily upon what I think is implicit in the reasoning of Jackson versus Denno and that is a realistic analysis of the fair trial situation in this kind of context where a jury is asked to do something that even a lawyer would find difficult or a judge would find difficult.","start":965.664,"stop":987.722,"duration":22.06},{"text":"There are no further questions on this issue I think I'll turn to right to lineup.","start":987.722,"stop":994.254,"duration":6.53},{"text":"Now, on the question of the right to counsel to lineup, I think it's clear from the briefs that I am attempting here to emphasize and perhaps to draw favoritism towards the amendment that I think is most important.","start":994.254,"stop":1003.84,"duration":9.59},{"text":"I am attempting to put this in a Sixth Amendment context.","start":1003.84,"stop":1008.137,"duration":4.3},{"text":"I think that there are decisions from this Court that hold amongst other things that the right to counsel is not limited to merely being an adjunct or protector of the Fifth Amendment.","start":1008.137,"stop":1016.896,"duration":8.76},{"text":"There are a number of decisions on that point.","start":1016.896,"stop":1018.821,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Obviously, in the in trial phase, the Sixth Amendment is not limited to protecting merely the Fifth.","start":1018.821,"stop":1024.298,"duration":5.48},{"text":"As Justice Friendly pointed out in one of the -- in a dissent in one of the companion cases to Gilbert, obviously, if we were in trial, the jury was selected, defense counsel standing there and it is suggested that the defendant adorned himself in a certain way, maybe wear a baseball cap if that's what the robber wore.","start":1024.298,"stop":1041.848,"duration":17.55},{"text":"That perhaps you could have them do this.","start":1041.848,"stop":1043.763,"duration":1.91},{"text":"There would be a question of the Fifth Amendment but holding there was no violation, you can have him do this.","start":1043.763,"stop":1047.843,"duration":4.08},{"text":"But it would not be proper to tell the counsel to excuse himself from the room because the Sixth Amendment would allow counsel -- would be present, observe the circumstances under which the test was performed, make appropriate comment to the jury, make his objections and I think the same point should be held here.","start":1047.843,"stop":1063.851,"duration":16.01},{"text":"I think that once you have judicial proceedings inaugurated and there is a difference of opinion amongst this Court as to when the right to counsel attaches but I think that once the judicial proceedings have inaugurate -- have been inaugurated, we've had an arraignment, we've had the appointment of an attorney, the probable cause necessary to reduce suspects down to one so that he's held for trial has already been passed upon.","start":1063.851,"stop":1084.707,"duration":20.86},{"text":"He's been arrested, he's been indicted, he's been arraigned --","start":1084.707,"stop":1086.566,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- do you know how far this goes Mr. McKissack?","start":1086.566,"stop":1088.477,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Do you say if --","start":1088.477,"stop":1088.58,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1088.58,"stop":1088.946,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- he's been indicted and been arraigned, then the police ought not to put him on a lineup at least without first providing him an opportunity to talk to a counsel?","start":1088.946,"stop":1097.517,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1097.517,"stop":1097.552,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that it?","start":1097.552,"stop":1098.613,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1098.613,"stop":1099.181,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I take if he had counsel --","start":1099.181,"stop":1101.007,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1101.007,"stop":1101.273,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the time he was in the lineup?","start":1101.273,"stop":1103.15,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1103.15,"stop":1104.058,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Appointed counsel?","start":1104.058,"stop":1105.056,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Appointed counsel and then relieved by privately obtained counsel the appointed --","start":1105.056,"stop":1108.427,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But in any event --","start":1108.427,"stop":1108.652,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- counsel --","start":1108.652,"stop":1109.391,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- so the police acknowledged he did have counsel?","start":1109.391,"stop":1110.954,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1110.954,"stop":1111.951,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And the police brought him and put him in the lineup --","start":1111.951,"stop":1114.191,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1114.191,"stop":1114.202,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- without affording him an opportunity to talk with counsel?","start":1114.202,"stop":1116.334,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"True.","start":1116.334,"stop":1116.647,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he ask to?","start":1116.647,"stop":1119.949,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question is really not to gone, too well in the state report.","start":1119.949,"stop":1126.324,"duration":6.38},{"text":"The opposition, the Attorney General of course cites the federal Gilbert case which runs along parallel to this for which he got 100 years and points out there that that he did ask for counsel and he was denied the right to it.","start":1126.324,"stop":1137.252,"duration":10.93},{"text":"As a matter of fact, I should point out that --","start":1137.252,"stop":1138.625,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is before then -- before you -- was put in the lineup and (Voice Overlap) --","start":1138.625,"stop":1141.817,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Before he was put in the --","start":1141.817,"stop":1142.858,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to consult his lawyer.","start":1142.858,"stop":1144.258,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1144.258,"stop":1144.312,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In which he knew he have a lawyer --","start":1144.312,"stop":1145.883,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1145.883,"stop":1145.919,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and he was refused.","start":1145.919,"stop":1147.116,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1147.116,"stop":1147.177,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1147.177,"stop":1148.457,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"And I should point out parenthetically for whatever its worth, there is a California statute which requires the intersession of a magistrate to determine whether or not a prisoner should be removed from the jail for any purpose and I would suggest that this is consistent with the notion that once a person is been arrested, he's been brought in and the judicial machinery has come into operation that a judge should at least be potentially available to rule upon any question is to how the defendant's going to spend his time or for what use he's going to be put.","start":1148.457,"stop":1175.603,"duration":27.15},{"text":"Now, the trust of the opposition briefs both the Government and the State of California is to try to limit the Sixth Amendment to be nothing more than a protector of the Fifth Amendment.","start":1175.603,"stop":1184.909,"duration":9.31},{"text":"And so their argument goes, let's see if there's a Fifth Amendment violation.","start":1184.909,"stop":1188.864,"duration":3.95},{"text":"Fifth Amendment violation, need counsel.","start":1188.864,"stop":1190.676,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you agree there's no Fifth Amendment violation?","start":1190.676,"stop":1192.846,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not agree with that, but I think that the Sixth Amendment argument is much clearer.","start":1192.846,"stop":1196.7,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does Schmerber have any bearing instead of --","start":1196.7,"stop":1198.66,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Schmerber certainly has a lot of bearing on the case.","start":1198.66,"stop":1200.509,"duration":1.85},{"text":"There's no question about that.","start":1200.509,"stop":1202.072,"duration":1.56},{"text":"I think it's distinguishable however.","start":1202.072,"stop":1205.127,"duration":3.06},{"text":"Schmerber is -- Your Honor would probably know better than anyone else, I think is a carefully drawn opinion trying to deal with the facts before it.","start":1205.127,"stop":1213.431,"duration":8.3},{"text":"We have a situation where the -- no judicial proceedings have been inaugurated.","start":1213.431,"stop":1216.784,"duration":3.35},{"text":"We had an arrest nothing further no complaint to the DA, no indictment or preliminary hearing or anything else to take the defendant into Court.","start":1216.784,"stop":1224.914,"duration":8.13},{"text":"We have a very reliable test involved, we have a doctor there taking a blood test and the simple question raised as I read the decision was, what's the effect of the defendant saying, “My counsel told me not to take the test”, and the Court held, well, since you didn't have a right not to take it, what harm was done by his refusal to take and not having counsel there.","start":1224.914,"stop":1246.689,"duration":21.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And the only distinction you make clear is that in this instance all this was done after indictment, after arraignment when you acknowledged of the police -- he in fact had counsel.","start":1246.689,"stop":1257.511,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the only distinction I would make but I don't think that that's a small one.","start":1257.511,"stop":1261.218,"duration":3.71},{"text":"I think it -- because it isn't -- the Court necessarily its -- itself in a situation where it must decide where the right to counsel attaches as far as I can see.","start":1261.218,"stop":1269.597,"duration":8.38},{"text":"All of these questions are going to raise Sixth Amendment questions.","start":1269.597,"stop":1272.164,"duration":2.57},{"text":"“Did you have counsel or not?”","start":1272.164,"stop":1273.856,"duration":1.69},{"text":"and involved -- just not -- just a narrow issue of Gilbert, but implicit here is what are you going to tie the right to counsel to him?","start":1273.856,"stop":1280.4,"duration":6.54},{"text":"If the Court is going to just say, “Alright, Schmerber interpreted meaning you have -- if you interpret it to mean that you only need the Sixth Amendment protection when you got a Fifth Amendment problem in a pretrial context, I think it leads to all kinds of problems”, because unlike to taking a blood which is either straight Fifth Amendment or not Fifth Amendment a lineup can be self-incriminatory or may not be.","start":1280.4,"stop":1301.937,"duration":21.54},{"text":"For example, if a man is put up in a lineup.","start":1301.937,"stop":1304.35,"duration":2.41},{"text":"And in this case, I contend some self-incriminatory question were asked, a man is put in the line up and he's asked, “Did he commit the crime?” and he says, “Yes, or no” this is a self-incriminatory question.","start":1304.35,"stop":1315.052,"duration":10.7},{"text":"And in this point here, everyone knew in the community you have 100 people in an auditorium all the potential eyewitnesses are thrown together.","start":1315.052,"stop":1323.419,"duration":8.37},{"text":"Everyone knew that Gilbert have been -- the robber have been arrested in Philadelphia.","start":1323.419,"stop":1327.328,"duration":3.91},{"text":"He was brought back here for identification and that the automobiles that were being driven and everything and that he was alarmed when arrested.","start":1327.328,"stop":1334.907,"duration":7.58},{"text":"He was asked questions in the lineup and this is in the state record.","start":1334.907,"stop":1338.554,"duration":3.65},{"text":"He's asked questions in the lineup, “Were you armed when you were arrested?”","start":1338.554,"stop":1342.052,"duration":3.5},{"text":"“Where were you arrested?”","start":1342.052,"stop":1343.826,"duration":1.77},{"text":"And “What automobile were you driving or what automobile do you own?”","start":1343.826,"stop":1347.393,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Now, this put Gilbert --","start":1347.393,"stop":1347.936,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the --","start":1347.936,"stop":1348.164,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the dilemma.","start":1348.164,"stop":1348.219,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the lineup itself were not -- is not in on itself involved Fifth Amendment problem.","start":1348.219,"stop":1355.184,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1355.184,"stop":1355.313,"duration":0.13},{"text":"I --","start":1355.313,"stop":1355.607,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Nothing in Schmerber suggests that asking question even when taking a blood test might not raise it.","start":1355.607,"stop":1362.269,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think that Schmerber goes nearly that far.","start":1362.269,"stop":1364.622,"duration":2.35},{"text":"At least I would hope that it would.","start":1364.622,"stop":1365.94,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't there a footnote there that leaves that open.","start":1365.94,"stop":1368.545,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1368.545,"stop":1369.589,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But there was no evidence -- offers with respect to statements in the lineup.","start":1369.589,"stop":1378.837,"duration":9.25}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was no evidence offered as to statements.","start":1378.837,"stop":1380.68,"duration":1.84},{"text":"So the issue would have to turn upon this, the bolstering and this I think would have to be determined upon remand.","start":1380.68,"stop":1390.455,"duration":9.77},{"text":"Potential eyewitnesses are brought to a lineup.","start":1390.455,"stop":1392.694,"duration":2.24},{"text":"The question is, can they identify Mr. Gilbert.","start":1392.694,"stop":1394.965,"duration":2.27},{"text":"In the course of this, I think certain self-incriminatory events occurred which I think undoubtedly would have contributed to their forming their opinion that this was undoubtedly the man.","start":1394.965,"stop":1405.082,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Now, actually at the time of the trial of course the witness points at the defendant and says, “Yes, that's the man”.","start":1405.082,"stop":1409.984,"duration":4.9},{"text":"But I think in effect we're going to have a question of an exclusionary rule or a poison fruit question which will ultimately come into play.","start":1409.984,"stop":1417.888,"duration":7.9},{"text":"But clearly, the eyewitness identification for the people dependent to some extent, how much extent this -- is we don't know.","start":1417.888,"stop":1425.113,"duration":7.23},{"text":"But to some extent --","start":1425.113,"stop":1425.201,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. McKissack, you say in any event on this -- confine the Sixth Amendment question.","start":1425.201,"stop":1432.754,"duration":7.55}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1432.754,"stop":1433.179,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That this stage in the proceeding, this was sufficiently a critical stage --","start":1433.179,"stop":1437.582,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1437.582,"stop":1438.1,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that he should not have been put the line up without an opportunity first to talk to his counsel?","start":1438.1,"stop":1442.193,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, that -- that's my point of view.","start":1442.193,"stop":1444.522,"duration":2.33},{"text":"I -- in fact if I may dwell upon that, I think that's the key that the right to counsel must be attached I think to a stage of the judicial proceedings, could be an Escobedo analysis where it be arrest, you take Massiah and make it perhaps an arraignment.","start":1444.522,"stop":1457.951,"duration":13.43},{"text":"It should be something that's traditional -- perennial that repeats itself in every case because there is an advantage to simplicity because you don't have errors and you don't have to worry about an excluding evidence.","start":1457.951,"stop":1467.169,"duration":9.22},{"text":"There's an advantage to making it's something that can be applied perspectively and understood by people who must apply it.","start":1467.169,"stop":1472.759,"duration":5.59},{"text":"These are necessarily values.","start":1472.759,"stop":1474.497,"duration":1.74},{"text":"I would suggest that tieing it to an Fifth Amendment question which is a very hairy question and Schmerber makes this clear.","start":1474.497,"stop":1480.463,"duration":5.97},{"text":"There are all kinds of situations that even maybe Fifth Amendment or not.","start":1480.463,"stop":1484.28,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what help can a lawyer give him beyond saying to him, answer no question?","start":1484.28,"stop":1491.623,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would suggest a number of reasons.","start":1491.623,"stop":1495.031,"duration":3.41},{"text":"He could for example if he was -- the client was going to the lineup, he could have a -- a motion's heard before a judge and perhaps ask a judge that certain questions not be asked.","start":1495.031,"stop":1504.65,"duration":9.62},{"text":"He can informally consult with the prosecutor and say, “Well, now what questions are you going to ask him?”","start":1504.65,"stop":1508.972,"duration":4.32},{"text":"So that if he is asking incriminating questions, he could say to the prosecutor, “Well, that's incriminating” and perhaps he would voluntarily withdraw his answer --","start":1508.972,"stop":1515.863,"duration":6.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That he could (Voice Overlap) --","start":1515.863,"stop":1515.885,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if not, he could instruct him not to answer --","start":1515.885,"stop":1516.967,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- he could say I take it, the lawyer couldn't -- if all that the police said they want to do is simply put the man in a lineup, the lawyer could not advised him not to stand in the lineup, could he?","start":1516.967,"stop":1530.003,"duration":13.04}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say that under decisions of this Court, the whole case and so forth that identification in the role without adornment so to speak would not obtain Fifth Amendment coverage, so I don't think I would have much optimism in making that point.","start":1530.003,"stop":1546.094,"duration":16.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I say.","start":1546.094,"stop":1546.753,"duration":0.66},{"text":"All actually, I suppose, the lawyer could say to him is keep your mouth shut, answer no questions.","start":1546.753,"stop":1551.036,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't think so at all.","start":1551.036,"stop":1552.393,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what else?","start":1552.393,"stop":1552.467,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I think --","start":1552.467,"stop":1553.059,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What else?","start":1553.059,"stop":1554.066,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are number of questions that could be asked as in this case --","start":1554.066,"stop":1556.778,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not questions.","start":1556.778,"stop":1558.546,"duration":1.77},{"text":"The lawyer says to him, “Answer no questions” and he says it to the district attorney?","start":1558.546,"stop":1564.275,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1564.275,"stop":1565.399,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, you put this --","start":1565.399,"stop":1565.963,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1565.963,"stop":1566.274,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- fellow on lineup, I've told them to answer no questions, so you asking him now.","start":1566.274,"stop":1570.316,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"That --","start":1570.316,"stop":1570.659,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can he do any more than that?","start":1570.659,"stop":1571.725,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he can.","start":1571.725,"stop":1572.453,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1572.453,"stop":1572.718,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case for example you had every single witness thrown into the same auditorium and there was a consensus identification.","start":1572.718,"stop":1578.641,"duration":5.92},{"text":"And each witness was asked to audibly speak out when they recognized the man, and you have eight or ten people appearing on the stage and they stand their own circle, may stand this way and then you see them from the front view.","start":1578.641,"stop":1587.659,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This was for voice identification?","start":1587.659,"stop":1589.255,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, for observation of their appearance and so forth.","start":1589.255,"stop":1593.772,"duration":4.52},{"text":"So whether this was the man you saw.","start":1593.772,"stop":1595.579,"duration":1.81},{"text":"Alright, now, one of the persons says, “Alright, its number 4, that's the man”.","start":1595.579,"stop":1599.719,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Well, you've got all of these other persons that are in there listening to it.","start":1599.719,"stop":1602.317,"duration":2.6},{"text":"As I pointed out in the brief, there are any number of reasons that would motivate a person then to be sure whether they weren't before joined the bandwagon technique, afraid that someone else is more perceptive than they are, variety of reasons that would lead a person to join with the same conclusion which had already been reached.","start":1602.317,"stop":1617.902,"duration":15.59},{"text":"Now, it's traditional --","start":1617.902,"stop":1618.083,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm trying to find out what the lawyer would do about it.","start":1618.083,"stop":1620.645,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"The lawyer could say to the prosecutor, “I think it would be a fair test if the witnesses were excluded which is a requirement under California law and in fact in most states, as far as I know, and let each witness come in one at a time and draw his own conclusions, and make his own identification.”","start":1620.645,"stop":1635.624,"duration":14.98},{"text":"Now, one thing that occurred to me en route to Washington on this matter is that -- I know the Government is emphasizing that counsel is more or less a rouge in a sense that the only thing he can do is to crap the case for the prosecution.","start":1635.624,"stop":1648.236,"duration":12.61},{"text":"But I'm suggesting that we have all kinds of precedent in our law, if we go outside the criminal appeal, for informal proceedings which don't necessarily leave the counsel becoming a harmful force.","start":1648.236,"stop":1657.781,"duration":9.54},{"text":"For example, in depositions, in civil cases, normally you just have two counsels present.","start":1657.781,"stop":1663.013,"duration":5.23},{"text":"You're entitled to make objections.","start":1663.013,"stop":1664.655,"duration":1.64},{"text":"Normally the objections are made and people are permitted to answer and then the judge will later make rulings on it.","start":1664.655,"stop":1669.827,"duration":5.17},{"text":"But I don't think that we can necessarily embrace the conclusion that because the prosecutor and defense counsel are there without the presence of a judge or the mandatory presence of a judge that it's necessary going to leave the hostility that some of these problems can't be worked out, that they won't agree that the witnesses should be segregated and so forth.","start":1669.827,"stop":1688.14,"duration":18.31},{"text":"Plus the fact you do have the added boon that the counsel is present, he observes what's going on and he is in a sense a talking witness to the fairness of the proceedings.","start":1688.14,"stop":1697.318,"duration":9.18},{"text":"And at this point I would call upon the strong language in Miranda which so eloquently suggests that having counsel present is a valid view when you're going to extract something.","start":1697.318,"stop":1707.675,"duration":10.36},{"text":"Now, of course, the taking of blood, it travels through -- let say, through a syringe and then into a tube and I don't suppose there's anything that counsel can do to interrupt this journey.But the -- if counsel is present, you're not going to have coerced confessions or certainly not as much as you would otherwise.","start":1707.675,"stop":1721.261,"duration":13.59},{"text":"Counsel, I think can present -- prevent this and if counsel is present, you're not as likely to have an unfair lineup which can be more factually and more accurately exploited at trial if it occurs.","start":1721.261,"stop":1731.907,"duration":10.65},{"text":"And if counsel just has to ask routine questions about well, where were people and so forth, he's on the scene and I suggest that counsel's presence is a positive benefit.","start":1731.907,"stop":1741.267,"duration":9.36},{"text":"And there's absolutely --","start":1741.267,"stop":1741.59,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what -- wouldn't all these arguments equally suggest there must be counsel at a lineup in advance of indictment?","start":1741.59,"stop":1751.553,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are we talking about after arrest or before arrest?","start":1751.553,"stop":1753.825,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"After arrest.","start":1753.825,"stop":1754.656,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"After arrest?","start":1754.656,"stop":1757.409,"duration":2.75},{"text":"Yes, I think that the -- I think that they would thrust themselves in that direction.","start":1757.409,"stop":1761.006,"duration":3.6},{"text":"But I do not feel that this Court would be required to say that because the same arguments would apply to a post arrest situation, pre-indictment, and necessarily we must decide that -- for example, if I may refer to be absent justice knowing -- the voting on Massiah and Escobedo, I don't think it would necessitate a conclusion that the rule should not be applied in this particular case.","start":1761.006,"stop":1785.582,"duration":24.58},{"text":"Because as I suggest in my brief, really all they (Inaudible) by the Government, suggesting that, “Well, why don't you have counsel on the scene at the time the defendants picked up as a suspect or where his fingerprinted here and then so forth?”","start":1785.582,"stop":1797.385,"duration":11.8},{"text":"These are not, as I see it, pointing out positive evils.","start":1797.385,"stop":1800.759,"duration":3.37},{"text":"These only points out the fact that our judicial system as is developed with the manpower available and under all the circumstances, we haven't found it either beneficial or necessary to supply counsel of that particular stage.","start":1800.759,"stop":1812.319,"duration":11.56},{"text":"I'm not of all convinced that it wouldn't be desirable in an ideal situation in a future situation that to have both the prosecutor and defense counsel present perhaps even a magistrate ideally, when ballistics test are made, when finger print tests are made and so forth.","start":1812.319,"stop":1827.557,"duration":15.24},{"text":"I'm not arguing for that proposition by -- I wish to point out that I think the fallacy committed by the opposition here is to try to carry our argument to such an extreme by labeling these occurrences as things that should not happen.","start":1827.557,"stop":1839.728,"duration":12.17},{"text":"And therefore concluded there's no real difference because it's still the same process, such a lineup no matter when it occurs and therefore there shouldn't be counsel in this case.","start":1839.728,"stop":1847.41,"duration":7.68},{"text":"I think that they don't point out that counsel shouldn't be present in the other cases it's just that we haven't found it necessary to attach counsel at that point.","start":1847.41,"stop":1855.826,"duration":8.42},{"text":"A consequence in this particular case of saying if we were to assume the opposite -- suppose we assumed that counsel should not be present at a lineup, then I think there's a great, great requirement here as to what -- what are the limitations of the right to counsel or when should he be present.","start":1855.826,"stop":1869.947,"duration":14.12},{"text":"We had the man arraigned, probable cause has been found, he's gone through an indictment or preliminary hearing, the next thing that is necessary is to stand trial.","start":1869.947,"stop":1878.068,"duration":8.12},{"text":"Now does this mean that the defendant then is in a sense -- can be conscript -- conscripted at any moment by the police out to take various test and without consultation of counsel and many of these tests may or may not involve the Fifth Amendment, that's the point I'm trying to bring in to play.","start":1878.068,"stop":1893.277,"duration":15.21},{"text":"Since --","start":1893.277,"stop":1893.305,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So, you're suggesting an -- a wholly automatic rule that counsel must be present during a lineup.","start":1893.305,"stop":1901.34,"duration":8.03},{"text":"And if he's not present during a lineup, any courtroom identification is tainted by the identification that the lineup which counsel wasn't present.","start":1901.34,"stop":1913.679,"duration":12.34}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Not quite, but I -- the first part of your statement I do agree with it.","start":1913.679,"stop":1916.26,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I am suggesting that --","start":1916.26,"stop":1917.14,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That not -- and it doesn't make any difference what actually happens at the lineup, whether it was fair, unfair or anything else.","start":1917.14,"stop":1922.687,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm not suggesting that.","start":1922.687,"stop":1924.844,"duration":2.16},{"text":"I am suggesting the first part of your statement.","start":1924.844,"stop":1926.647,"duration":1.8},{"text":"A categorical rule for counsel, a lineup is a right.","start":1926.647,"stop":1929.706,"duration":3.06},{"text":"Now, I would agree that then there's a separate question that if there's a violation of the right, what's the consequence?","start":1929.706,"stop":1934.516,"duration":4.81},{"text":"I think that there should be a right to counsel.","start":1934.516,"stop":1936.376,"duration":1.86},{"text":"I always -- I don't think this Court should lay down a rule that we're going to retroactively determine whether counsel should've been present because of what happened.","start":1936.376,"stop":1943.272,"duration":6.9},{"text":"I think this Court should say that counsel after he's been arraigned, has a -- it should -- has a right to be present or his presence is waived.","start":1943.272,"stop":1950.275,"duration":7},{"text":"Then comes the question which Your Honors been dwelling upon and that is what's the effect of him not being there?","start":1950.275,"stop":1955.263,"duration":4.99},{"text":"And if I were to address myself to that, the Court would have I think a choice between a categorical rule which would be to say if it were an in-trial court situation, the case would automatically be reversed.","start":1955.263,"stop":1967.144,"duration":11.88},{"text":"As a matter of fact, in Hamilton versus Alabama the situation where the counsel was not present in the arraignment, they have a reversal of the death penalty murder case and I point out that in Hamilton none of the rights which are pointed out as making it a critical stage of the Alabama arraignment procedure, none of these rights were necessarily constitutional rights.","start":1967.144,"stop":1987.338,"duration":20.19},{"text":"So this is another example of the fact that counsel in that case was not there just to protect the Fifth Amendment.","start":1987.338,"stop":1991.713,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you do have to reach this in your case because if --","start":1991.713,"stop":1994.714,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1994.714,"stop":1994.925,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- unless there's a categorical rule you have to get to the facts to this case --","start":1994.925,"stop":1998.452,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":1998.452,"stop":1998.624,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whether there's some unfairness at the lineup.","start":1998.624,"stop":2000.609,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2000.609,"stop":2001.766,"duration":1.16},{"text":"I don't think there's any question about it.","start":2001.766,"stop":2003.047,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I think that you have to get to the --","start":2003.047,"stop":2004.032,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you contending for, the categorical rule?","start":2004.032,"stop":2006.131,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2006.131,"stop":2006.398,"duration":0.27},{"text":"I am contending obviously all throughout the categorical rule as a possibility because in the arguments for that are number one, this is a simple requirement.","start":2006.398,"stop":2014.41,"duration":8.01},{"text":"Now, anybody I think can follow it.","start":2014.41,"stop":2016.354,"duration":1.94},{"text":"Once he's been arraigned, he can have a counsel.","start":2016.354,"stop":2018.012,"duration":1.66},{"text":"There should be no future violations of the law in this field under the vague contours of due process, yes, but not in this area.","start":2018.012,"stop":2024.674,"duration":6.66},{"text":"So, I think simplicity can require a more rigid rule.","start":2024.674,"stop":2027.312,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Now, the rule that I would advocate if the Court doesn't accept it is the one that's been urged in dissenting opinions in the Gilbert federal case by Justice Browning and in the White case by Judge Bazelon and that is that it's a question of the -- a taint, to what extent has the eyewitness identification been bolstered or contaminated by what occurred at the lineup.","start":2027.312,"stop":2048.143,"duration":20.83},{"text":"And I think that if the Court adopted that view it would require a remand to this case.","start":2048.143,"stop":2051.254,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that sort of a Betts and Brady approach to the right of counsel at the lineup?","start":2051.254,"stop":2058.418,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is a Betts and Brady approach.","start":2058.418,"stop":2060.178,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you, you're going to all through that again?","start":2060.178,"stop":2062.451,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I wouldn't advocate it if we do.","start":2062.451,"stop":2064.025,"duration":1.57},{"text":"In other words, my position is where simplicity can be exacted, simplicity should be required.","start":2064.025,"stop":2069.045,"duration":5.02},{"text":"There's no reason at all we should have this problem ever arise if we hold that counsel is required after arraignment.","start":2069.045,"stop":2075.956,"duration":6.91},{"text":"But the reason for Betts and Brady approach, I think that Betts versus Brady's approach is not bad.","start":2075.956,"stop":2080.493,"duration":4.54},{"text":"It just shouldn't have been the case and right to counsel in Betts versus Brady.","start":2080.493,"stop":2083.953,"duration":3.46},{"text":"The reason why the Court might hold that Betts versus Brady is applicable here is that you might hold it is just too severe to say that because there was a denial of right to counsel, that you're going to throw out the case because all these witnesses can't testify.","start":2083.953,"stop":2097.135,"duration":13.18},{"text":"And if the Court test feels that's too severe, then I think we've got to look for a moderate rule in between --","start":2097.135,"stop":2102.327,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think --","start":2102.327,"stop":2102.35,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because it's also not fair -- yes.","start":2102.35,"stop":2103.784,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it's too severe?","start":2103.784,"stop":2105.904,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's too severe because of the fact that it can be applied with simplicity.","start":2105.904,"stop":2110.676,"duration":4.77},{"text":"If these were a vague test and it could not be adhered to.","start":2110.676,"stop":2114.12,"duration":3.44},{"text":"If these were like some of the questions of search and seizure, or like the Fifth Amendment, I would find it a little bit too severe, frankly put.","start":2114.12,"stop":2122.13,"duration":8.01},{"text":"But I think that the -- just like in the Sixth Amendment right to counsel cases, I think that every single -- if counsel goes -- if a defendant goes to trial and he's never asked if he wants an attorney and he goes through it, there's no way where I think it should be reversed and there should never be an inquiry to prejudice.","start":2122.13,"stop":2137.936,"duration":15.81},{"text":"Why not, because he may not have been prejudiced, but I don't think the rule is so drastic.","start":2137.936,"stop":2141.848,"duration":3.91},{"text":"I think he can be complied with.","start":2141.848,"stop":2143.687,"duration":1.84},{"text":"And this is a thrust of my whole argument in this case where I'm trying to keep the Sixth Amendment clear of the Fifth, because if you're going to attach the Sixth to the Fifth, you've got to make a retroactive determination of whether the Fifth was violated before he decided, whether he should've had the Sixth Amendment right to counsel which must -- a decision which must be made before the Fifth Amendment comes into play.","start":2143.687,"stop":2161.569,"duration":17.88},{"text":"And that's what I want to avoid.","start":2161.569,"stop":2163.463,"duration":1.89},{"text":"But if we take the middle rule, I would suggest that it would have to be remanded where a determination as to whether or not the in court eyewitness identification was substantially and I realize this is a vague term affected by the proceedings at the lineup.","start":2163.463,"stop":2179.635,"duration":16.17},{"text":"But I don't think it's any more of vague test than -- we have to say a poison tree -- a fruit language, where all the Court can really do is to sort of put a verbal standard out and roughly suggest what the Court is trying to suggest.","start":2179.635,"stop":2191.457,"duration":11.82},{"text":"That is that a tainted fruit of an illegal search should not be introduced.","start":2191.457,"stop":2195.275,"duration":3.82},{"text":"But recognizing that this principle can go too far, a language is thrown out about so attenuated as to dissipate the taint.","start":2195.275,"stop":2202.875,"duration":7.6},{"text":"It's impossible to pin that down as to what it means but it does indicate that there comes a point where you can go too far.","start":2202.875,"stop":2209.417,"duration":6.54},{"text":"And so I would suggest if the Court took the middle position that the case should be remanded, so that a full pledged hearing can be heard on exactly what happened at the lineup -- whether self-incrimination is involved and so forth.","start":2209.417,"stop":2220.899,"duration":11.48},{"text":"But the prejudice -- prejudicial factors that came into play, whether the witnesses' opinion as to -- whether they saw Gilbert was in fact fortified, bolstered, or made by what they saw at the lineup.","start":2220.899,"stop":2233.163,"duration":12.26},{"text":"And I think that's the thrust of my contention.","start":2233.163,"stop":2235.055,"duration":1.89},{"text":"It's not the answer of the Sixth Amendment to the Fifth, but let it stand as it is because it's a simple requirement and I think it's an important one.","start":2235.055,"stop":2241.881,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But what if it was that the -- what if a -- what if the courtroom identification rested a deal on memories of a fellow -- that the witness knew the -- identified this person once before at the lineup and he real -- and he -- and has been quite a while and so he does rely on the -- on his lineup identification.","start":2241.881,"stop":2266.91,"duration":25.03},{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2266.91,"stop":2268.842,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think then in that case the testimony should be excluded.","start":2268.842,"stop":2272.283,"duration":3.44},{"text":"I would say this that --","start":2272.283,"stop":2273.694,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Because there wasn't counsel present.","start":2273.694,"stop":2275.566,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Because there wasn't counsel present.","start":2275.566,"stop":2276.591,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's assume counsel was present.","start":2276.591,"stop":2278.673,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2278.673,"stop":2279.288,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And then the witness testifies at the trial.","start":2279.288,"stop":2282.323,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2282.323,"stop":2282.86,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so -- but it says, “Well, do you -- are you relying on your lineup identification?”","start":2282.86,"stop":2288.17,"duration":5.31},{"text":"He answers, “Well, yes, yes.”","start":2288.17,"stop":2290.262,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- then I'm --","start":2290.262,"stop":2290.811,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) to mind a good deal, “I identified the man?","start":2290.811,"stop":2293.481,"duration":2.67},{"text":"I identify -- identify him now.\"","start":2293.481,"stop":2295.333,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"There should be no reversal because it would then be a question of whether the Fifth Amendment was violated.","start":2295.333,"stop":2300.549,"duration":5.22},{"text":"If their right to counsel is satisfied by having counsel present, there's nothing in the world wrong with the witness for having his testimony bolstered or affected by what occurred at the lineup because I would contend that a lineup just by itself is not illegal and there's nothing to taint the identification, the mere fact that they formed their opinion there as far as I can see it, there's nothing illegal in that.","start":2300.549,"stop":2319.785,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seems, Mr. McKissack, I gather you do say if there's no counsel present and then on your middle rule, that there is some finding of taint --","start":2319.785,"stop":2327.764,"duration":7.98}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2327.764,"stop":2328.321,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- then you exclude what?","start":2328.321,"stop":2329.889,"duration":1.57},{"text":"All evidence of identification by the witness?","start":2329.889,"stop":2333.09,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Suppose the witness --","start":2333.09,"stop":2333.425,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2333.425,"stop":2334.335,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2334.335,"stop":2334.375,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"If by that particular witness, yes.","start":2334.375,"stop":2336.223,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the -- in other words, the only question that this attorney asked the witness was, “Can you identify the man you saw at the place of the robbery?”","start":2336.223,"stop":2345.705,"duration":9.48},{"text":"“Yes” “Is he in the courtroom?”","start":2345.705,"stop":2346.824,"duration":1.12},{"text":"“Yes.”","start":2346.824,"stop":2347.095,"duration":0.27},{"text":"“Where is he?”","start":2347.095,"stop":2347.574,"duration":0.48},{"text":"“Over there.”","start":2347.574,"stop":2348.423,"duration":0.85},{"text":"You wouldn't allow him that much.","start":2348.423,"stop":2351.594,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- well, if it was -- it was premised upon -- no, it would require an interrogation into what actually happened at the lineup.","start":2351.594,"stop":2358.059,"duration":6.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, I'm assuming now that he --","start":2358.059,"stop":2359.502,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he is --","start":2359.502,"stop":2359.921,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2359.921,"stop":2360.272,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that if -- alright, if the witness answered, “Well, I saw the man at the bank, the next time I saw him was at --","start":2360.272,"stop":2368.279,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he didn't answer that.","start":2368.279,"stop":2369.258,"duration":0.98},{"text":"The only answer is this, “Yes, I saw him at the bank.\"","start":2369.258,"stop":2371.479,"duration":2.22},{"text":"\"Where is he?\"","start":2371.479,"stop":2371.934,"duration":0.46},{"text":"\"Sitting over there alongside counsel.\"","start":2371.934,"stop":2375.259,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And then on cross-examination.","start":2375.259,"stop":2377.881,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2377.881,"stop":2378.162,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"On cross-examination, defense counsel taints it.","start":2378.162,"stop":2381.828,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"If defense counsel taints it, then I think that it should go out and I can't think of a better place to do it than on a cross and probably occurs more there than any other time.","start":2381.828,"stop":2388.353,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2388.353,"stop":2389.431,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that it should go out under those circumstances.","start":2389.431,"stop":2393.908,"duration":4.48},{"text":"The one thing I would encourage -- well, that I would encourage --","start":2393.908,"stop":2396.107,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact, the first question is, in that circumstance the judge can throw it out and he has to declare in this trial and prosecute, he couldn't possibly -- to get the witness testimony.","start":2396.107,"stop":2410.443,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then the -- I see what you mean.","start":2410.443,"stop":2412.087,"duration":1.64},{"text":"I think there would -- well, one problem of course is yes.","start":2412.087,"stop":2419.254,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Once this rule is announced, it then becomes forecast for all judges and lawyers to know about.","start":2419.254,"stop":2423.929,"duration":4.68},{"text":"And I would think that the prosecution would be mindful of the law as well as anyone else.","start":2423.929,"stop":2429.448,"duration":5.52},{"text":"All we really -- all I'm really asking for you is -- yes sir, the prosecution -- they have the defendant list away without checking with counsel and put him at the lineup, the penalty that it would have to be paid is that if the testimony that was obtained to which -- which is given at trial were shown to have been premised upon something that occurred at the lineup and that was where they fortified their opinion that it should be excluded.","start":2429.448,"stop":2450.455,"duration":21.01},{"text":"But I don't see any particular (Inaudible) in the -- of course, I would be asking in this case for the proposition that cases that decide the law first announced it.","start":2450.455,"stop":2458.741,"duration":8.29},{"text":"It should certainly be applied retroactively because this encourages defendants to come before the Court and I think it's largely explanatory for the development in the -- in this particular field of civil liberties in the last 15 years.","start":2458.741,"stop":2469.394,"duration":10.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what if the witness' testimony at the trial was pretty well premised upon identification from photographs, that the police showed up, and counsel wasn't present?","start":2469.394,"stop":2484.218,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm looking at right to counsel in terms of occurring at a stage and not the process.","start":2484.218,"stop":2488.456,"duration":4.24},{"text":"I -- in other words, I --","start":2488.456,"stop":2490.256,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, (Voice Overlap) after indictment?","start":2490.256,"stop":2492.262,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"After indictment looking at the photograph.","start":2492.262,"stop":2493.313,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"After indictment and the witnesses looked at some photographs.","start":2493.313,"stop":2496.958,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, my answer --","start":2496.958,"stop":2497.436,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the man.","start":2497.436,"stop":2498.799,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"My answer to that is this --","start":2498.799,"stop":2498.996,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) anywhere.","start":2498.996,"stop":2500.506,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"My answer to that is this.","start":2500.506,"stop":2501.926,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Although it makes -- although it is not traditional and I realized that the Court would probably not make any matter of constitutional law.","start":2501.926,"stop":2507.237,"duration":5.31},{"text":"There's no positive harm in having counsel present to determine whether one photograph is singled out.","start":2507.237,"stop":2512.442,"duration":5.2},{"text":"A number of photographs are singled out.","start":2512.442,"stop":2513.296,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, I'm not -- I'm not suggesting there's positive harm on this -- but with rule -- would you apply the rule to the photograph situation?","start":2513.296,"stop":2520.159,"duration":6.86}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think the Court would go that far, so I wouldn't ask the Court to go that far.","start":2520.159,"stop":2523.482,"duration":3.32},{"text":"I think ideally that that there's a lot of harm that can be done in doing photographs, not as much as a lineup because there defendants being interrogated and it may turn out when we look at it with hindsight that he didn't incriminate himself.","start":2523.482,"stop":2534.84,"duration":11.36},{"text":"What he said was just say voice identification or he's standing there with a hat on.","start":2534.84,"stop":2538.678,"duration":3.84},{"text":"But that can't occur with photographs.","start":2538.678,"stop":2542.092,"duration":3.41},{"text":"There are two differences.","start":2542.092,"stop":2542.865,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Number one, the defendant doesn't speak so what he says can incriminate himself, can hurt him otherwise.","start":2542.865,"stop":2547.969,"duration":5.1},{"text":"And number two, I think when you got control of the defendant, there are number of things he might do to injure his case without the presence of counsel that he can't do and he's nothing but a picture on a page.","start":2547.969,"stop":2558.229,"duration":10.26},{"text":"But for example, in Gilbert's case as a -- one of the witnesses pointed out this -- that he seemed a little reluctant to speak, or he was very soft and looks like he's trying to avoid the question.","start":2558.229,"stop":2568.154,"duration":9.93},{"text":"Now this can in a sense, tend to be self-incriminatory because he feels he's got something to hide and therefore he shows nervous etcetera.","start":2568.154,"stop":2575.113,"duration":6.96},{"text":"So, I think you have some distinctions but I think the argument of the Court would be that if these are parallel, that is you're looking at someone in a lineup, you're looking at someone in a photo, that it doesn't necessarily lead to the conclusion that because we have not attached the right to counsel when a photograph is being examined, we're not going to do it whether there's a lineup involved.","start":2575.113,"stop":2592.288,"duration":17.18},{"text":"They are the differences I've pointed out plus the fact that we have just not held that is necessary or that critical that a defendant counsel be present when a photograph is taken.","start":2592.288,"stop":2605.45,"duration":13.16},{"text":"And I would again refer to what the language of -- matching of cases on irrelevant facts.","start":2605.45,"stop":2610.401,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I think the critical thing here is to gear the Sixth Amendment to a phase of the proceedings and not direct to whether it's going to be a photographs, a lineup, handwriting exemplars, blood tests, and so forth.","start":2610.401,"stop":2620.62,"duration":10.22},{"text":"I feel that that's going to involved -- you need a prospective analysis and that's going to involve a lot of questions and those -- those categories all over them are not entities.","start":2620.62,"stop":2628.194,"duration":7.57},{"text":"They may either be self-incriminatory, they'll be harmful for other reasons and they aren't necessarily entities.","start":2628.194,"stop":2633.832,"duration":5.64},{"text":"And I would point out there are some precedent because in England, the Solicitor attends lineups and I don't think there's any showing that the English judicial system -- interrogation is broken down, and we have it on -- in the City of Philadelphia a similar example.","start":2633.832,"stop":2648.555,"duration":14.72},{"text":"And as I say in the State of California, the statute was violated but called for a judge to make a determination as to whether Mr. Gilbert should've been wished away for any purpose, lineup, or otherwise.","start":2648.555,"stop":2660.203,"duration":11.65},{"text":"Now, on the question of the Fifth Amendment, I would just make one comment on the right to lineup.","start":2660.203,"stop":2663.464,"duration":3.26},{"text":"I think that there were at least two or three incriminating comments that were obtained.","start":2663.464,"stop":2668.608,"duration":5.14},{"text":"When he's asked where he was arrested, he's in a dilemma.","start":2668.608,"stop":2671.19,"duration":2.58},{"text":"If he answers truthfully, he says, “Philadelphia” the witnesses there know the robber was arrested in Philadelphia.","start":2671.19,"stop":2675.526,"duration":4.34},{"text":"If he answers falsely, that if he knows the smattering of law or even from common sense, he may assume that it could be used against him in trial which we would call impeachment.","start":2675.526,"stop":2683.331,"duration":7.81},{"text":"He's asked what kind of a car he owns.","start":2683.331,"stop":2684.712,"duration":1.38},{"text":"If he names the right car, he names the car of the robber.","start":2684.712,"stop":2688.114,"duration":3.4},{"text":"He's -- he was also asked whether he was armed at the time.","start":2688.114,"stop":2691.298,"duration":3.18},{"text":"And in this trial, and the California Court held this to be erroneously admitted, it was pointed out that he own the 45 -- he had a 45 weapon on him at the time that he was apprehended.","start":2691.298,"stop":2700.56,"duration":9.26},{"text":"They held this was error and as a matter of fact the policeman was killed by a 45 weapon.","start":2700.56,"stop":2704.962,"duration":4.4},{"text":"And at the lineup, one of the questions was asked, “Were you armed?”","start":2704.962,"stop":2707.542,"duration":2.58},{"text":"If he answers, “Yes”, he says, “45 weapon”, this is incriminatory, besides, it makes him a suicidal menace.","start":2707.542,"stop":2712.628,"duration":5.09},{"text":"And in addition, the fact that he's apprehended in Philadelphia when the crime occurs in California suggest to the witnesses, the perspective witnesses, that this is (Inaudible), and that's also harmful to him.","start":2712.628,"stop":2723.539,"duration":10.91},{"text":"So, I feel that this is another advantage of the Sixth Amendment.","start":2723.539,"stop":2726.771,"duration":3.23},{"text":"Counsel might have been able to consult with the district attorney and say, “Alright, we'll segregate the witnesses.","start":2726.771,"stop":2731.685,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Let them make identifications one by one”.","start":2731.685,"stop":2734.861,"duration":3.18},{"text":"Maybe after this is done, if there's a value that can sense his identification, they could all be grouped into the same room.","start":2734.861,"stop":2740.554,"duration":5.69},{"text":"And then they can make identification.","start":2740.554,"stop":2742.423,"duration":1.87},{"text":"But I think the counsel could have assured that, he could have prevented the self-incriminatory questions.","start":2742.423,"stop":2746.867,"duration":4.44},{"text":"One thing I do seek to avoid is that in -- depending upon whether it's a Stovall or Wade case, there have been -- the lower court has criticized the position I have taken particularly, people speaking against the position, by I think reducing it to an absurdity and making them take the position they don't take, like what's counsel going to do, tell the defendant to wear a mask?","start":2746.867,"stop":2766.179,"duration":19.31},{"text":"I'm not urging that.","start":2766.179,"stop":2766.957,"duration":0.78},{"text":"But, what's he's going to do?","start":2766.957,"stop":2768.296,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Just tell him not to go there at all?","start":2768.296,"stop":2771.125,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Our position is not bottomed on those assumptions.","start":2771.125,"stop":2773.272,"duration":2.15},{"text":"It's bottomed on the fact that predictability is a value.","start":2773.272,"stop":2776.354,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Having counsel there, we may clean up a lot of these problems and if may call to mind, one of the cases I heard this morning, it's like a San Francisco or Washington ordinance case.","start":2776.354,"stop":2786.064,"duration":9.71},{"text":"If you find as a matter of empirical fact that everyone is consenting to something and there's no real problem, then -- you know, you would have evaluate it in terms of circumstances you actually find and we should encourage here as little violations of law and Fifth Amendment problems as possible.","start":2786.064,"stop":2801.963,"duration":15.9},{"text":"And the presence of counsel I think would point towards us in.","start":2801.963,"stop":2807.231,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Probably I just point out that I think Miranda doesn't subject counsel into the interrogation process because they realize that there's a value in having there and the same argument would make for this case.","start":2807.231,"stop":2815.993,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"When did --","start":2815.993,"stop":2816.296,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2816.296,"stop":2816.412,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the question of harmless error come in the case, are you defending on this?","start":2816.412,"stop":2821.206,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I depending on harmless error?","start":2821.206,"stop":2822.518,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you defending to any extent on that doctrine in this case?","start":2822.518,"stop":2828.664,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2828.664,"stop":2829.388,"duration":0.72},{"text":"I -- perhaps each question involved here would have to evaluated differently.","start":2829.388,"stop":2834.469,"duration":5.08},{"text":"But the Court would have of course had a choice as to what kind of test it would apply in the lineup situation.","start":2834.469,"stop":2840.195,"duration":5.73},{"text":"If they were in counsel, obviously, ipso facto reversal of this before you could -- if you choose a Fahy like test, I would suggest that when we're talking about the Sixth Amendment with something so easily to comply with that we should have across the board test.","start":2840.195,"stop":2853.227,"duration":13.03},{"text":"If not, we're talking about the effect of the error and the choice is to either treat this case as I say, and I think it should be treated as the case that makes the lawyer enunciates the rule as a value and not inquiring -- introduce your prejudice to support this, historically, we've never done that.","start":2853.227,"stop":2868.871,"duration":15.64},{"text":"In Griffin versus California, they -- well, it could've been asked, “Alright, suppose there was comment, now, what's the effect of it?”","start":2868.871,"stop":2874.338,"duration":5.47},{"text":"The Court hasn't done it.","start":2874.338,"stop":2875.704,"duration":1.37},{"text":"And I think that there is a value to not doing it this particular case but the Court could at the same time suggest that obviously maybe there'd be a de minimis rule so that -- if there's a tiniest infraction of the law, a case shouldn't be reversed.","start":2875.704,"stop":2887.746,"duration":12.04},{"text":"I think that those points of view can be squared quite easily.","start":2887.746,"stop":2892.98,"duration":5.23},{"text":"Now, if I may turn to the handwriting exemplar argument, on the Sixth Amendment, I think we can just simply state this is the lineup question except for the fact that where in Escobedo situation and not in Massiah.","start":2892.98,"stop":2907.56,"duration":14.58},{"text":"And the question would be, “What is the difference between a person under arrest and a person who has been arraigned?”","start":2907.56,"stop":2912.155,"duration":4.6},{"text":"And I think that this is been fully briefed and the Court has considered this and that the only thing I can say is that there is a difference clearly between say an arraignment situation and a post arrest situation.","start":2912.155,"stop":2924.923,"duration":12.77},{"text":"There, we know there's a great difference, where they're searching to see if a crime is committed and trying to find out who committed it, a lot of questions can be asked and properly so.Scenes can be surveyed, pictures can be taken, a lot of things can be done.","start":2924.923,"stop":2936.089,"duration":11.17},{"text":"Once he's focused, once a person is arrested, once there's probable cause, then we get into an area where perhaps the right to counsel should attach.","start":2936.089,"stop":2943.024,"duration":6.93},{"text":"I would argue that the right to counsel should attach.","start":2943.024,"stop":2945.433,"duration":2.41},{"text":"But I would -- at the same time maintain that if it doesn't attach at the time that defendant has been arrested, it certainly should attach the time that he's gone before a -- there's been a grand jury indictment, he's been informed against -- an informal judicial proceedings have begun.","start":2945.433,"stop":2959.254,"duration":13.82},{"text":"And I would point out on the Fifth Amendment involving handwriting exemplars, that -- there has been a suggestion previously about lie detectors, perhaps this is protected by the Fifth Amendment while other forms of evidence aren't.","start":2959.254,"stop":2970.682,"duration":11.43},{"text":"I think this is very tricky and very difficult question.","start":2970.682,"stop":2973.437,"duration":2.76},{"text":"I think the handwriting exemplar could be viewed either way.","start":2973.437,"stop":2977.411,"duration":3.97},{"text":"Certainly, it's different than taking the blood in some senses, the question is, “Is the difference does or not to a distinction or the other way around?”","start":2977.411,"stop":2983.721,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, am I right that most of authorities have had considered it, had believed it was not testimonial and therefore not a Fifth Amendment?","start":2983.721,"stop":2991.491,"duration":7.77}]},{"speakerName":"Luke McKissack","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think its simple majority at least to the persons who have inherently study handwriting would analogize it, at least to fingerprinting, and think that it would identify a person, but not all the courts.","start":2991.491,"stop":3002.259,"duration":10.77},{"text":"And in an area like this, I think it would commit the Court too an examination of the scientific data, the moment of time to decide if that was in fact the case.","start":3002.259,"stop":3011.732,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Plus the fact that you may assume that even if it was scientific, it doesn't necessarily mean that it is not self-incriminatory.","start":3011.732,"stop":3018.199,"duration":6.47},{"text":"I think upon probing into it that the Fifth Amendment to some extent just rest upon this rule -- concerns and is nonetheless for it.","start":3018.199,"stop":3026.065,"duration":7.87},{"text":"I think that there are some facets of it that is difficult to analytically tie down to some particular purpose.","start":3026.065,"stop":3032.851,"duration":6.79},{"text":"It's not purely a question of how scientific a test is.","start":3032.851,"stop":3036.149,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Its -- can be expressed in the popular jargon, we don't cause people to dig their own graves and this has a meaning to some people.","start":3036.149,"stop":3041.989,"duration":5.84},{"text":"And in fact I would point out that in the philosophical literature in the field of criminal law, the English philosopher H.L.A. Hart is probably dedicated and made his greatest contribution by pointing out that many of our criminal laws are not -- many of our criminal laws are not premised entirely upon the ideas that we think, they are like deterrents.","start":3041.989,"stop":3062.057,"duration":20.07},{"text":"For example, you've got a question of insanity or drunkenness, the old utilitarian school of Jeremy Bentham which say, “Give him a steeper penalty”, and the analysis shows that the reason we treat insane people lightly is not because an across-the-board penalty wouldn't be a better deterrent because its only -- maybe one or two, he would feign insanity or creep within the category he might be deterred.","start":3062.057,"stop":3082.96,"duration":20.9},{"text":"But we do it because of the considerations that we think its right.","start":3082.96,"stop":3085.893,"duration":2.93},{"text":"It just seems to square with our notions or our values at a given moment in time.","start":3085.893,"stop":3089.475,"duration":3.58},{"text":"The same distinction between, say omissions and acts, a person shoots the man on the beach that's murder.","start":3089.475,"stop":3094.469,"duration":4.99},{"text":"If he sees the man drowning, he doesn't rescue him, and the person is not a relative or friend, it's an omission to act.","start":3094.469,"stop":3099.7,"duration":5.23},{"text":"It maybe reprehensible but we don't classify it the same way.","start":3099.7,"stop":3102.82,"duration":3.12},{"text":"And I think that there is a guttural or literal premise under the Fifth Amendment that we can't fight -- put our hands on.","start":3102.82,"stop":3108.675,"duration":5.86},{"text":"And so, it just doesn't require an analysis of how scientific evidence is.","start":3108.675,"stop":3112.456,"duration":3.78},{"text":"In handwriting, the defendant is required to actively procure evidence against himself.","start":3112.456,"stop":3116.683,"duration":4.23},{"text":"He has to create evidence that didn't otherwise exist and even though as I would concede, these factors of this rule, I think that it does go into the question because it coincides of what people think about what the Fifth Amendment ought to be.","start":3116.683,"stop":3131.188,"duration":14.51},{"text":"And I think that's fair.","start":3131.188,"stop":3132.352,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now Mr. --","start":3132.352,"stop":3135.502,"duration":3.15}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Case pending","arguedOn":"Feb  15 - 16, 1967","petitioner":"Jesse James Gilbert","respondent":"California","docket":"223","citation":"388 US 263 (1967)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/388/263","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"Jun 13, 1966","decidedOn":"Jun 12, 1967"}